r species before further reduction to methanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis of C1-C3 oxygenated compounds from CO2/H2 on magnetite has been reported by McCollom & Seewald (2003, Earth and Planetary Science Letters) and He et al. (2019, PNAS). Formaldehyde production, though fleeting, is documented as a transient intermediate in these systems (Kopetzki & Antonietti, 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from C1 building blocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mineral surface-catalyzed aldol-type condensation under reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate and formaldehyde undergo sequential condensation and carbonylation reactions on iron-sulfide mineral surfaces. The pathway proceeds via glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde intermediates (not isolated), which undergo further oxidation/rearrangement to yield pyruvate. The FeS2 surface stabilizes the carbonyl intermediates and promotes C-C bond formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cody et al. (2000, Science) demonstrated pyruvate formation from C1 precursors under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions with FeS catalysts at 250\u00b0C and 2000 bar. Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) showed that native iron and iron minerals can fix CO2 to pyruvate under mild hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) confirmed pyruvate as a central product of Fe0-driven CO2 fixation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"proto-reductive TCA cycle analog, sequential carboxylation via oxaloacetate intermediate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate is carboxylated to oxaloacetate on the greigite surface (analogous to the reverse TCA step), then further reduced and carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This two-step process mirrors the biological reductive TCA cycle. The mineral surfaces stabilize the keto-acid intermediates and provide electrons from H2 for the reductive steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated a complete non-enzymatic analog of the reductive TCA cycle driven by Fe0 and Fe3S4, producing all key intermediates including \u03b1-ketoglutarate from pyruvate and CO2. Varma et al. (2018) confirmed these transformations under mild hydrothermal conditions. This represents one of the strongest cases for a geochemical origin of central metabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH3-rich alkaline vent fluids, mineral-catalyzed reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks the C2 carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate, which is then reduced by H2 on the pyrite surface to yield glutamate. This mirrors the biological glutamate dehydrogenase reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Letters) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) showed that iron minerals catalyze amino acid synthesis from keto acids and NH3. Kitadai et al. (2018, Science Advances) confirmed reductive amination on various mineral surfaces at hydrothermal temperatures.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Extended Strecker synthesis of glutamate from C1 units and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool environment, multi-step Strecker via succinaldehyde-like intermediates, moderate HCN concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In an extended Strecker pathway, formaldehyde undergoes aldol self-condensation to C2-C4 aldehydes on clay surfaces. The C4 succinate semialdehyde reacts with HCN and NH3 in a classical Strecker sequence: aldehyde + NH3 \u2192 imine, imine + HCN \u2192 aminonitrile, aminonitrile hydrolysis \u2192 glutamic acid. Montmorillonite concentrates and orients reactants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the most robust prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Miller, 1957; Cleaves et al., 2008). Extended Strecker synthesis of higher amino acids from HCN and aldehydes has been demonstrated by Lerner et al. (1993, PNAS) and is supported by the detection of glutamic acid in Strecker reaction mixtures (Pizzarello & Shock, 2010). Clay-catalyzed concentration is supported by Ferris et al. (1996, Nature).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of glutamate to glutamic gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reducing conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal system, selective gamma-carboxyl reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on Fe0/magnetite surfaces. Fe0 acts as a two-electron donor, reducing the carboxylic acid to the aldehyde oxidation state via a surface-bound acyl intermediate. The \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxyl groups are protected by chelation to the mineral surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Selective reduction of carboxylic acids to aldehydes on iron mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions has been documented by Wang et al. (2011). This reaction parallels the biological glutamate-5-semialdehyde dehydrogenase step in the ornithine biosynthetic pathway. The reducing power of Fe0 for selective organic reductions is well-established (Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of glutamic gamma-semialdehyde to ornithine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, transamination/reductive amination at the delta-aldehyde position\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-aldehyde of glutamic semialdehyde reacts with ammonia to form a Schiff base at the \u03b4-position, which is then reduced (by pyrite-mediated electron transfer or by disproportionation) to produce the \u03b4-amino group of ornithine. The clay surface concentrates reactants and may facilitate imine reduction through surface-mediated H-transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of aldehydes by ammonia is one of the most fundamental prebiotic amino group installation reactions (Barge et al., 2019). The conversion of glutamic semialdehyde to ornithine mirrors the biological pathway (ornithine aminotransferase). Transamination reactions on mineral surfaces have been demonstrated by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) and Kitadai (2015, Astrobiology).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photochemical synthesis of cyanamide from HCN and NH3\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow evaporitic pool, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN is photooxidized on TiO2 surfaces under UV irradiation. The photogenerated holes on TiO2 abstract an electron from HCN, producing a cyanide radical (CN\u2022) which couples with NH2\u2022 (from NH3 photolysis) to form cyanamide (H2N-CN). Alternatively, HCN undergoes direct photochemical reaction with NH3 to produce cyanamide plus H2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanamide is a key prebiotic condensing and guanidinating agent. Its formation from HCN photochemistry is supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry) and by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) in the cyanosulfidic scenario. TiO2 photocatalysis of HCN derivatives has been demonstrated by Sasselov et al. (Rimmer et al., 2018, Science Advances). Cyanamide has also been detected in interstellar medium.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven hydrolysis of HCN to urea\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, aqueous HCN solution, proceeds via formamide and isocyanic acid intermediates, NH3 present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN is first hydrated to formamide (HCONH2) either photochemically or thermally. Formamide undergoes UV-driven decomposition to isocyanic acid (HNCO), which reacts with ambient NH3 to produce urea (H2N-CO-NH2). TiO2 photocatalysis accelerates the initial HCN hydration step. Alternatively, two equivalents of formamide condense to form urea directly under UV/thermal conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide-to-urea conversion under UV irradiation is well-documented (Saladino et al., 2012, Chemistry & Biodiversity). The HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 urea pathway has been extensively studied by Saladino, Di Mauro and colleagues. Isocyanic acid + NH3 \u2192 urea was demonstrated by Lohrmann & Orgel (1971). Urea is a key prebiotic reagent found in meteorites and produced abundantly from HCN solutions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (optional)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 8-9, concentrated pool conditions, reaction time days to weeks\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine performs a nucleophilic addition to the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). This produces an intermediate guanidine via a direct addition-tautomerization mechanism: Orn-NH2 + H2N-CN \u2192 Orn-NH-C(=NH)-NH2. The product is arginine with the characteristic guanidinium side chain.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanamide-mediated guanidination of amines is a well-established prebiotic reaction (Steinman et al., 1964, Science; Osterberg et al., 1973). The reaction of ornithine with cyanamide to produce arginine has been directly demonstrated by Steinman et al. (1964) under mild aqueous conditions. This is considered one of the most plausible prebiotic routes to arginine (Higgs & Pudritz, 2009, Astrobiology; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine carbamylation by urea to citrulline and subsequent amination to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (struvite)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"struvite (MgNH4PO4\u00b76H2O)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool, phosphate-mediated activation of urea, 2-step: ornithine+urea\u2192citrulline, then citrulline+NH3\u2192arginine under dry heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: Under drying conditions, urea is activated (possibly via isocyanate intermediate HNCO) and reacts with the \u03b4-amino group of ornithine to form the ureido bond of citrulline. Phosphate minerals may catalyze the dehydration of urea. Step 2: In the subsequent wetting cycle, citrulline is aminated at the ureido carbonyl by NH3 under mild heating, converting the ureido group to the guanidinium group of arginine. This mirrors the biological urea cycle in reverse.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The urea-cycle-like conversion of ornithine \u2192 citrulline \u2192 arginine is biosynthetically universal, suggesting deep prebiotic roots (de Duve, 1991). Prebiotic ureido bond formation from urea and amines under wet-dry conditions has been demonstrated (Lohrmann & Orgel, 1971; Leman et al., 2004). Phosphate-mediated activation of urea is supported by Gibard et al. (2018, Nature Chemistry). The conversion of citrulline to arginine under prebiotic conditions, while less studied, is thermodynamically favorable with ammonia as nitrogen donor.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA to glutamate to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination (via formate)\",\n      \"description\": \"Full hydrothermal carbon fixation path through formate and formaldehyde to pyruvate, then proto-rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, reduction and transamination to ornithine, with final cyanamide-mediated guanidination to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA to glutamate to ornithine, urea/citrulline pathway (via formate)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same hydrothermal backbone as P1 but the guanidinium group is installed via the urea/citrulline route rather than direct cyanamide guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker glutamate, hydrothermal ornithine synthesis, cyanamide guanidination\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate is produced via extended Strecker synthesis on clay surfaces from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia. Glutamate is then processed hydrothermally to glutamic semialdehyde, followed by surface transamination to ornithine and cyanamide guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker glutamate, hydrothermal ornithine synthesis, urea/citrulline pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Strecker-derived glutamate feeds into hydrothermal ornithine synthesis, with the guanidinium group installed through the urea-citrulline-arginine route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate-only route to pyruvate, rTCA, reductive amination, cyanamide guanidination\",\n      \"description\": \"Emphasizes formate as the sole C1 starting unit from hydrothermal CO2 reduction, feeding both the pyruvate synthesis (via formaldehyde from rxn_002) and the rTCA pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT formaldehyde hub pathway with Strecker and cyanamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis serves as the hub: feeds Strecker synthesis (\u2192glutamate) and combines with formate for pyruvate. Both routes converge at glutamate. Cyanamide finishes the arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-centric pathway: Strecker glutamate + cyanamide from same HCN pool\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN serves as the hub molecule providing both the carbon/nitrogen for Strecker amino acid synthesis and the guanidinating agent (cyanamide). This pathway highlights HCN as the master prebiotic reagent.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-centric pathway: Strecker glutamate + urea from HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN provides both the amino acid backbone (via Strecker) and the guanidinium nitrogen (via urea from HCN hydrolysis). Alternative endpoint installation through citrulline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed environment: hydrothermal alpha-ketoglutarate, surface amination, cyanamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate is synthesized hydrothermally from pyruvate, exported to surface where reductive amination (on clays) produces glutamate. Ornithine is made at the surface, and cyanamide guanidination completes arginine in a prebiotic pool.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergent pathway: hydrothermal + Strecker glutamate, dual guanidination\",\n      \"description\": \"Both hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker synthesis produce glutamate (convergence point). Both cyanamide and urea/citrulline pathways operate in parallel (second convergence at arginine). This represents the full redundant network operating simultaneously.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate: central metabolic hub formed hydrothermally, feeds into proto-rTCA cycle\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate: key convergence point from two independent synthetic routes (hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker synthesis)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Ornithine: direct precursor to arginine, converges with two guanidinating agents (cyanamide, urea) leading to two routes to arginine\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde: C1 hub molecule used in both pyruvate synthesis and Strecker synthesis routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Arginine: target molecule reached by two independent guanidination pathways (cyanamide direct and urea/citrulline)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "Arginine (C6H14N4O2) is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network centered on ornithine as the key penultimate intermediate. The guanidinium group of arginine is installed via reaction of ornithine with cyanamide (direct guanidination) or through a urea/citrulline pathway. Ornithine itself derives from glutamate, which is produced either by reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate (generated via hydrothermal CO2 fixation through a proto-rTCA pathway) or via extended Strecker-type synthesis from HCN and formaldehyde. The network integrates hydrothermal CO2 reduction (formate, formaldehyde, pyruvate), surface photochemistry (cyanamide, urea from HCN), and biochemical assembly (guanidination, condensation). Five hub molecules\u2014HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, glutamate, and ornithine\u2014create a densely interconnected network with multiple redundant routes to the target.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "5-amino-2-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamic gamma-semialdehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H12N2O2", "iupac_name": "2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "urea", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H13N3O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(carbamoylamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "citrulline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-9-5(8)10/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H3,8,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is adsorbed onto the Fe3S4 greigite surface, which acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. Hydride transfer from H2 (activated on the mineral surface) reduces CO2 to formate (HCOO-) via a two-electron reduction.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) and Roldan et al. (2015, Chemical Communications) under simulated alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions. This reaction is thermodynamically favorable given the high H2 concentrations produced by serpentinization."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type CO2 reduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal systems"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is first reduced to CO on Fe0 surfaces, then CO is hydrogenated to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces. Formaldehyde is a key C1 intermediate that can be trapped by reaction with other species before further reduction to methanol.", "reasoning": "FTT synthesis of C1-C3 oxygenated compounds from CO2/H2 on magnetite has been reported by McCollom & Seewald (2003, Earth and Planetary Science Letters) and He et al. (2019, PNAS). Formaldehyde production, though fleeting, is documented as a transient intermediate in these systems (Kopetzki & Antonietti, 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Pyruvate synthesis from C1 building blocks", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite and greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "mineral surface-catalyzed aldol-type condensation under reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Formate and formaldehyde undergo sequential condensation and carbonylation reactions on iron-sulfide mineral surfaces. The pathway proceeds via glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde intermediates (not isolated), which undergo further oxidation/rearrangement to yield pyruvate. The FeS2 surface stabilizes the carbonyl intermediates and promotes C-C bond formation.", "reasoning": "Cody et al. (2000, Science) demonstrated pyruvate formation from C1 precursors under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions with FeS catalysts at 250\u00b0C and 2000 bar. Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) showed that native iron and iron minerals can fix CO2 to pyruvate under mild hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) confirmed pyruvate as a central product of Fe0-driven CO2 fixation."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "proto-reductive TCA cycle analog, sequential carboxylation via oxaloacetate intermediate"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate is carboxylated to oxaloacetate on the greigite surface (analogous to the reverse TCA step), then further reduced and carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This two-step process mirrors the biological reductive TCA cycle. The mineral surfaces stabilize the keto-acid intermediates and provide electrons from H2 for the reductive steps.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated a complete non-enzymatic analog of the reductive TCA cycle driven by Fe0 and Fe3S4, producing all key intermediates including \u03b1-ketoglutarate from pyruvate and CO2. Varma et al. (2018) confirmed these transformations under mild hydrothermal conditions. This represents one of the strongest cases for a geochemical origin of central metabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH3-rich alkaline vent fluids, mineral-catalyzed reductive amination"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks the C2 carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate, which is then reduced by H2 on the pyrite surface to yield glutamate. This mirrors the biological glutamate dehydrogenase reaction.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Letters) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) showed that iron minerals catalyze amino acid synthesis from keto acids and NH3. Kitadai et al. (2018, Science Advances) confirmed reductive amination on various mineral surfaces at hydrothermal temperatures."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Extended Strecker synthesis of glutamate from C1 units and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "evaporitic pool environment, multi-step Strecker via succinaldehyde-like intermediates, moderate HCN concentration"}, "mechanism": "In an extended Strecker pathway, formaldehyde undergoes aldol self-condensation to C2-C4 aldehydes on clay surfaces. The C4 succinate semialdehyde reacts with HCN and NH3 in a classical Strecker sequence: aldehyde + NH3 \u2192 imine, imine + HCN \u2192 aminonitrile, aminonitrile hydrolysis \u2192 glutamic acid. Montmorillonite concentrates and orients reactants.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the most robust prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Miller, 1957; Cleaves et al., 2008). Extended Strecker synthesis of higher amino acids from HCN and aldehydes has been demonstrated by Lerner et al. (1993, PNAS) and is supported by the detection of glutamic acid in Strecker reaction mixtures (Pizzarello & Shock, 2010). Clay-catalyzed concentration is supported by Ferris et al. (1996, Nature)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Reduction of glutamate to glutamic gamma-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": true, "other": "reducing conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal system, selective gamma-carboxyl reduction"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on Fe0/magnetite surfaces. Fe0 acts as a two-electron donor, reducing the carboxylic acid to the aldehyde oxidation state via a surface-bound acyl intermediate. The \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxyl groups are protected by chelation to the mineral surface.", "reasoning": "Selective reduction of carboxylic acids to aldehydes on iron mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions has been documented by Wang et al. (2011). This reaction parallels the biological glutamate-5-semialdehyde dehydrogenase step in the ornithine biosynthetic pathway. The reducing power of Fe0 for selective organic reductions is well-established (Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Transamination of glutamic gamma-semialdehyde to ornithine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "evaporitic pool, transamination/reductive amination at the delta-aldehyde position"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-aldehyde of glutamic semialdehyde reacts with ammonia to form a Schiff base at the \u03b4-position, which is then reduced (by pyrite-mediated electron transfer or by disproportionation) to produce the \u03b4-amino group of ornithine. The clay surface concentrates reactants and may facilitate imine reduction through surface-mediated H-transfer.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of aldehydes by ammonia is one of the most fundamental prebiotic amino group installation reactions (Barge et al., 2019). The conversion of glutamic semialdehyde to ornithine mirrors the biological pathway (ornithine aminotransferase). Transamination reactions on mineral surfaces have been demonstrated by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) and Kitadai (2015, Astrobiology)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "UV photochemical synthesis of cyanamide from HCN and NH3", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow evaporitic pool, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "HCN is photooxidized on TiO2 surfaces under UV irradiation. The photogenerated holes on TiO2 abstract an electron from HCN, producing a cyanide radical (CN\u2022) which couples with NH2\u2022 (from NH3 photolysis) to form cyanamide (H2N-CN). Alternatively, HCN undergoes direct photochemical reaction with NH3 to produce cyanamide plus H2.", "reasoning": "Cyanamide is a key prebiotic condensing and guanidinating agent. Its formation from HCN photochemistry is supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry) and by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) in the cyanosulfidic scenario. TiO2 photocatalysis of HCN derivatives has been demonstrated by Sasselov et al. (Rimmer et al., 2018, Science Advances). Cyanamide has also been detected in interstellar medium."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "UV-driven hydrolysis of HCN to urea", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, aqueous HCN solution, proceeds via formamide and isocyanic acid intermediates, NH3 present"}, "mechanism": "HCN is first hydrated to formamide (HCONH2) either photochemically or thermally. Formamide undergoes UV-driven decomposition to isocyanic acid (HNCO), which reacts with ambient NH3 to produce urea (H2N-CO-NH2). TiO2 photocatalysis accelerates the initial HCN hydration step. Alternatively, two equivalents of formamide condense to form urea directly under UV/thermal conditions.", "reasoning": "Formamide-to-urea conversion under UV irradiation is well-documented (Saladino et al., 2012, Chemistry & Biodiversity). The HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 urea pathway has been extensively studied by Saladino, Di Mauro and colleagues. Isocyanic acid + NH3 \u2192 urea was demonstrated by Lohrmann & Orgel (1971). Urea is a key prebiotic reagent found in meteorites and produced abundantly from HCN solutions."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Direct guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (optional)", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly alkaline pH 8-9, concentrated pool conditions, reaction time days to weeks"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine performs a nucleophilic addition to the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). This produces an intermediate guanidine via a direct addition-tautomerization mechanism: Orn-NH2 + H2N-CN \u2192 Orn-NH-C(=NH)-NH2. The product is arginine with the characteristic guanidinium side chain.", "reasoning": "Cyanamide-mediated guanidination of amines is a well-established prebiotic reaction (Steinman et al., 1964, Science; Osterberg et al., 1973). The reaction of ornithine with cyanamide to produce arginine has been directly demonstrated by Steinman et al. (1964) under mild aqueous conditions. This is considered one of the most plausible prebiotic routes to arginine (Higgs & Pudritz, 2009, Astrobiology; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Ornithine carbamylation by urea to citrulline and subsequent amination to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (struvite)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "struvite (MgNH4PO4\u00b76H2O)", "aqueous": true, "other": "wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool, phosphate-mediated activation of urea, 2-step: ornithine+urea\u2192citrulline, then citrulline+NH3\u2192arginine under dry heating"}, "mechanism": "Step 1: Under drying conditions, urea is activated (possibly via isocyanate intermediate HNCO) and reacts with the \u03b4-amino group of ornithine to form the ureido bond of citrulline. Phosphate minerals may catalyze the dehydration of urea. Step 2: In the subsequent wetting cycle, citrulline is aminated at the ureido carbonyl by NH3 under mild heating, converting the ureido group to the guanidinium group of arginine. This mirrors the biological urea cycle in reverse.", "reasoning": "The urea-cycle-like conversion of ornithine \u2192 citrulline \u2192 arginine is biosynthetically universal, suggesting deep prebiotic roots (de Duve, 1991). Prebiotic ureido bond formation from urea and amines under wet-dry conditions has been demonstrated (Lohrmann & Orgel, 1971; Leman et al., 2004). Phosphate-mediated activation of urea is supported by Gibard et al. (2018, Nature Chemistry). The conversion of citrulline to arginine under prebiotic conditions, while less studied, is thermodynamically favorable with ammonia as nitrogen donor."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal rTCA to glutamate to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination (via formate)", "description": "Full hydrothermal carbon fixation path through formate and formaldehyde to pyruvate, then proto-rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, reduction and transamination to ornithine, with final cyanamide-mediated guanidination to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal rTCA to glutamate to ornithine, urea/citrulline pathway (via formate)", "description": "Same hydrothermal backbone as P1 but the guanidinium group is installed via the urea/citrulline route rather than direct cyanamide guanidination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Surface Strecker glutamate, hydrothermal ornithine synthesis, cyanamide guanidination", "description": "Glutamate is produced via extended Strecker synthesis on clay surfaces from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia. Glutamate is then processed hydrothermally to glutamic semialdehyde, followed by surface transamination to ornithine and cyanamide guanidination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Surface Strecker glutamate, hydrothermal ornithine synthesis, urea/citrulline pathway", "description": "Strecker-derived glutamate feeds into hydrothermal ornithine synthesis, with the guanidinium group installed through the urea-citrulline-arginine route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal formate-only route to pyruvate, rTCA, reductive amination, cyanamide guanidination", "description": "Emphasizes formate as the sole C1 starting unit from hydrothermal CO2 reduction, feeding both the pyruvate synthesis (via formaldehyde from rxn_002) and the rTCA pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "FTT formaldehyde hub pathway with Strecker and cyanamide", "description": "Formaldehyde from Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis serves as the hub: feeds Strecker synthesis (\u2192glutamate) and combines with formate for pyruvate. Both routes converge at glutamate. Cyanamide finishes the arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "HCN-centric pathway: Strecker glutamate + cyanamide from same HCN pool", "description": "HCN serves as the hub molecule providing both the carbon/nitrogen for Strecker amino acid synthesis and the guanidinating agent (cyanamide). This pathway highlights HCN as the master prebiotic reagent.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "HCN-centric pathway: Strecker glutamate + urea from HCN", "description": "HCN provides both the amino acid backbone (via Strecker) and the guanidinium nitrogen (via urea from HCN hydrolysis). Alternative endpoint installation through citrulline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Mixed environment: hydrothermal alpha-ketoglutarate, surface amination, cyanamide", "description": "Alpha-ketoglutarate is synthesized hydrothermally from pyruvate, exported to surface where reductive amination (on clays) produces glutamate. Ornithine is made at the surface, and cyanamide guanidination completes arginine in a prebiotic pool.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Dual-convergent pathway: hydrothermal + Strecker glutamate, dual guanidination", "description": "Both hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker synthesis produce glutamate (convergence point). Both cyanamide and urea/citrulline pathways operate in parallel (second convergence at arginine). This represents the full redundant network operating simultaneously.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Pyruvate: central metabolic hub formed hydrothermally, feeds into proto-rTCA cycle", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Glutamate: key convergence point from two independent synthetic routes (hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker synthesis)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Ornithine: direct precursor to arginine, converges with two guanidinating agents (cyanamide, urea) leading to two routes to arginine", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_005", "description": "Formaldehyde: C1 hub molecule used in both pyruvate synthesis and Strecker synthesis routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "Arginine: target molecule reached by two independent guanidination pathways (cyanamide direct and urea/citrulline)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": []}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 404075.57797431946, "success": true, "error_message": null}
