way_id\": \"P6\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-architected synthesis network for arginine that demonstrates genuine strategic improvements over naive approaches: the glutamate\u2192GABA\u21924-aminobutanal route avoids direct gamma-carboxyl reduction selectivity issues, and the cyanamide guanidination is the correct prebiotic approach. The network has strong topology with 18 molecules, 16 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points creating meaningful redundancy. The rTCA chemistry core (rxn_003, 006-008, 010) is well-supported by literature. Two critical bottlenecks persist across ALL pathways and cannot be circumvented within the current network architecture: (1) rxn_013 \u2014 the carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction of GABA on mackinawite lacks strong experimental precedent for selective partial reduction stopping at the aldehyde, and (2) rxn_015 \u2014 cyanamide formation from HCN + NH3 under UV is mechanistically uncertain (photochemistry of HCN more commonly yields oligomeric products or formamide rather than cyanamide). Since every pathway to arginine must traverse both rxn_013 and rxn_015, these are network-level vulnerabilities. Addressing either one \u2014 e.g., by providing an alternative ornithine source that bypasses 4-aminobutanal, or an alternative guanidinium donor with better-documented formation \u2014 would push the network above the approval threshold. The best pathway P6 achieves borderline approval at 0.80 by minimizing additional weak steps.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.80,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.84\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.88, "rxn_002": 0.65, "rxn_004": 0.85, "rxn_005": 0.72, "rxn_006": 0.8, "rxn_007": 0.75, "rxn_008": 0.76, "rxn_010": 0.82, "rxn_012": 0.8, "rxn_013": 0.55, "rxn_014": 0.7, "rxn_015": 0.58, "rxn_016": 0.87}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.72, "pathway_coherence": 0.8, "environmen