reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Arginine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.7\n- Feedback: This is a thoughtfully designed synthesis network for arginine with strong conceptual foundations. The five hub molecules (HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, glutamate, ornithine) are well-chosen and create meaningful convergence points. The overall strategy of building ornithine from glutamate and then installing the guanidinium group via cyanamide is sound and aligns with both biosynthetic logic and known prebiotic chemistry. However, three persistent chemical issues prevent approval: (1) The C1\u2192C3 pyruvate synthesis (rxn_003) and C3\u2192C5 alpha-ketoglutarate synthesis (rxn_004) are oversimplified \u2014 each requires at minimum one additional explicit intermediate. (2) The selective reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to semialdehyde (rxn_007) is the most problematic step \u2014 this is thermodynamically uphill and kinetically demanding without enzymatic activation. Alternative routes to ornithine (e.g., via diaminobutyrate homologation or direct Strecker-type synthesis of ornithine from an appropriate aldehyde) should be explored. (3) The urea/citrulline\u2192arginine conversion (rxn_012) lacks a clear prebiotic mechanism for the final amination step. The cyanamide guanidination route is significantly more defensible. Mineral catalysts are not specified for any reaction, which weakens the environmental grounding. Despite these issues, the network topology and strategic design are strong (0.85), and with refinement of 3-4 key reactions, this network could reach the approval threshold.\n- Issues: ['Strongest environmental progression (H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B). CO2 reduction to formate is well-supported, but pyruvate synthesis from formate+formaldehyde (rxn_003) is a significant chemical leap requiring several implicit intermediates. The C3\u2192C5 reductive carboxylation (rxn_004) also skips oxaloacetate. Most critically, selective reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to semialdehyde (rxn_007) is thermodynamically and kinetically challenging without enzymatic activation. Final guanidination by cyanamide (rxn_011) is well-documented prebiotically.', 'Shares the same problematic early steps as P1. The urea/citrulline route (rxn_012) is weaker than direct cyanamide guanidination because conversion of citrulline to arginine requires an activated nitrogen source (not just NH3). Biochemically this step requires ATP and aspartate; prebiotically the mechanism is unclear. Having citrulline and arginine as co-products in one step is chemically unjustified.', 'Shorter pathway is appealing but rxn_006 (extended Strecker to glutamate) is poorly defined \u2014 building a C5 amino acid from C1 units in a single step requires multiple implicit aldol condensations plus a Strecker reaction. The environmental flow (S\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B) is less clean than P1. The glutamate-to-ornithine conversion (rxn_007, rxn_008) remains the weak link.', 'Combines the weaknesses of P3 (extended Strecker) with the problematic urea/citrulline route. Least viable of the main pathways. Environmental progression is also mixed.', 'Very similar to P1, emphasizing formate as the sole CO2 reduction product. Avoids the need for FTT formaldehyde (rxn_002) but still requires formaldehyde for rxn_003. Essentially this pathway needs better definition of how formaldehyde enters if not through rxn_002.', 'Formaldehyde as the central hub feeding into Strecker chemistry is conceptually elegant. However, rxn_006 remains the bottleneck \u2014 building glutamate from formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 in one step is a major oversimplification. The H\u2192S\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B flow is acceptable.', 'HCN serving as both the carbon backbone source (Strecker) and guanidinium donor (cyanamide) is a strong conceptual framework. The dual-use of HCN is prebiotically elegant. However, chemical execution issues in rxn_006 and rxn_007 lower the score. The most conceptually unified pathway.', 'HCN-centric variant using the weaker urea/citrulline route. Combines the Strecker oversimplification with the problematic rxn_012. Less viable than P7.', 'Best mixed-environment pathway. Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces alpha-ketoglutarate, then surface amination and guanidination complete the synthesis. Notably bypasses the problematic glutamate\u2192semialdehyde reduction (rxn_007) if surface amination is performed differently. However, the pathway description suggests it still passes through ornithine, so rxn_007/rxn_008 may still be needed. The best environmental flow among all pathways.', \"The dual-convergent pathway leverages redundancy from both hydrothermal and Strecker routes to glutamate, and both guanidination pathways. While maximizing network robustness, it inherits all the chemical weaknesses of the component pathways. The redundancy concept is sound for prebiotic plausibility arguments but doesn't improve the chemical feasibility of the weakest steps.\"]\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: This is a well-architected synthesis network for arginine that demonstrates genuine strategic improvements over naive approaches: the glutamate\u2192GABA\u21924-aminobutanal route avoids direct gamma-carboxyl reduction selectivity issues, and the cyanamide guanidination is the correct prebiotic approach. The network has strong topology with 18 molecules, 16 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points creating meaningful redundancy. The rTCA chemistry core (rxn_003, 006-008, 010) is well-supported by literature. Two critical bottlenecks persist across ALL pathways and cannot be circumvented within the current network architecture: (1) rxn_013 \u2014 the carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction of GABA on mackinawite lacks strong experimental precedent for selective partial reduction stopping at the aldehyde, and (2) rxn_015 \u2014 cyanamide formation from HCN + NH3 under UV is mechanistically uncertain (photochemistry of HCN more commonly yields oligomeric products or formamide rather than cyanamide). Since every pathway to arginine must traverse both rxn_013 and rxn_015, these are network-level vulnerabilities. Addressing either one \u2014 e.g., by providing an alternative ornithine source that bypasses 4-aminobutanal, or an alternative guanidinium donor with better-documented formation \u2014 would push the network above the approval threshold. The best pathway P6 achieves borderline approval at 0.80 by minimizing additional weak steps.\n- Issues: ['Longest pathway with the most reaction steps; includes the weak formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_002) and the thermodynamically problematic GABA carboxyl reduction (rxn_013). Multiple hydrothermal-surface transitions weaken the environmental narrative. The chain of 13 steps means cumulative yield issues are significant.', 'Eliminates the weak formate\u2192formaldehyde step by using direct CO2\u2192pyruvate on native iron. Cleaner environmental flow with a long hydrothermal block followed by surface chemistry and biochemical finish. Still bottlenecked by rxn_013 (GABA reduction) and rxn_015 (cyanamide formation).', 'Combines the weakest elements: formate\u2192formaldehyde (rxn_002), succinate\u2192succinic semialdehyde (rxn_009), and GABA reduction (rxn_013). Three separate carboxyl/carbonyl reduction bottlenecks make this the least chemically robust route. The Strecker synthesis of glutamate from succinic semialdehyde (rxn_011) is itself sound, but producing the aldehyde substrate is the problem.', 'Hybrid route using direct pyruvate synthesis and Strecker glutamate. Still suffers from succinate\u2192succinic semialdehyde (rxn_009) and GABA reduction (rxn_013). Two separate difficult carboxyl reductions lower confidence.', 'Formaldehyde-centric buildup showcases the C1\u2192C2\u2192C3\u2192C5 logic well. Includes the formate reduction step which is moderate risk. Same terminal bottlenecks as other pathways (rxn_013, rxn_015).', \"Dual-HCN route using Strecker chemistry twice. Elegant in concept but doubles down on the difficult succinate\u2192succinic semialdehyde reduction. The dual use of HCN is a nice thematic element but doesn't solve the thermodynamic bottlenecks.\", 'Longest formate-based route combined with the Strecker glutamate branch. Accumulates the most problematic steps (rxn_002, rxn_009, rxn_013, rxn_015). Too many weak links for high confidence.', 'Succinate branching pathway demonstrates network redundancy by exploring both branches from the succinate hub. Useful for showing convergence but inherits the weaknesses of both branches simultaneously.', 'Explicitly designed to showcase the Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical environmental cycle. Best environmental narrative among all pathways. The back-and-forth is justified by the chemistry: C1 fixation (hydrothermal), aldol (surface), carbonylation+rTCA (hydrothermal), decarboxylation+Strecker (surface), guanidination (biochemical). Still limited by the same terminal bottlenecks.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Arginine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network constructs arginine (2-amino-5-guanidinopentanoic acid) through two convergent branches: (1) ornithine synthesis via either a hydrothermal rTCA-to-glutamate route with surface photocatalytic reduction, or an alternative surface-based succinaldehyde-Strecker route that completely bypasses the problematic enzymatic-type carboxyl reductions of prior attempts; and (2) cyanamide synthesis via urea thermal dehydration (well-documented) with urea itself accessible from two independent routes (direct hydrothermal CO2+NH3 and surface formamide+NH3). The final guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide is a well-established organic transformation. Five hub molecules (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, ornithine, urea) create network density with multiple convergent and divergent connections. The succinaldehyde-Strecker route to ornithine (via UV radical coupling of acetaldehyde followed by selective mono-reductive amination and Strecker synthesis) provides a novel bypass of the glutamate-5-semialdehyde bottleneck identified in prior attempts. Environmental flow proceeds from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through surface photochemistry and wet-dry cycling to biochemical assembly.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h4H,1-3,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,5-diaminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ornithine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"common_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H14N4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"arginine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs onto the Fe3S4 surface, which structurally and functionally mimics biological [Fe4S4] clusters. Surface-bound H2 dissociates heterolytically. Hydride transfer to adsorbed CO2 produces formate (HCOO-). This is a two-electron reduction proceeding through a surface-bound carboxyl radical intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is one of the best-documented prebiotic reactions. Roldan et al. (2015, Chem. Commun.) demonstrated CO2 reduction to formate on greigite surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Preiner et al. (2020, Life) showed H2-dependent CO2 reduction on Fe3S4 at 100\u00b0C producing formate as the primary C1 product. The structural analogy between greigite and biological ferredoxin [Fe4S4] clusters supports the plausibility of this reaction as a primordial carbon fixation step (Russell & Martin, 2004, Trends Biochem. Sci.).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4) with mackinawite (FeS) co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Requires strong reducing conditions; H2 partial pressure >10 bar\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbs on magnetite surface through carboxylate coordination to Fe sites. Dissociated H2 on FeS provides hydride. Two-electron reduction of formate proceeds through a hydroxymethyl intermediate, losing water to yield formaldehyde. The reaction is thermodynamically uphill (\u0394G ~ +30 kJ/mol) but driven by high H2 fugacity and continuous product removal by downstream reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formate-to-formaldehyde reduction is thermodynamically challenging but documented under extreme hydrothermal conditions. He et al. (2019, PNAS) showed that native iron and iron oxides can reduce formate at elevated pressures. The high H2 fugacity in serpentinization systems (McCollom & Seewald, 2007, Elements) provides the thermodynamic driving force. This step is the kinetic bottleneck of the C1 pathway and operates at lower yields than rxn_003.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO2 reduction to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe0) with Ni traces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fe0 acts as both reductant and catalyst; may involve awaruite (Ni3Fe)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Native iron (Fe0) provides reducing equivalents through oxidation to Fe2+. CO2 undergoes stepwise reduction: CO2 \u2192 CO \u2192 HCOH. The Fe0 surface activates CO2 through back-donation into the \u03c0* orbital, weakening C=O bonds. Formaldehyde is released as the surface is re-reduced by dissolved H2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron under hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, moderate pressure) reduces CO2 to a range of products including formaldehyde, acetate, and pyruvate. Fe0 provides a stronger thermodynamic driving force than Fe3S4, enabling direct access to more reduced C1 products. This represents a convergent route to formaldehyde alongside the formate reduction pathway (rxn_002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4) with trace Ni\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions; CO from hydrothermal degassing or CO2 reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"On the magnetite surface, CO undergoes dissociative adsorption to form surface carbide and oxide species. Stepwise hydrogenation of surface carbide produces surface methyl (CH3*) and surface methylene (CH2*) species. Formaldehyde provides an additional C1 unit via carbonyl insertion into the surface C-H bond, yielding a surface-bound acetaldehyde species that desorbs. Alternatively, CO inserts into a surface Fe-CH3 bond, followed by hydrogenation to give acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite and other iron minerals is well-documented. McCollom et al. (1999, Origins Life Evol. Biosphere) and Holm & Andersson (2005, Astrobiology) showed that FTT reactions at hydrothermal vent conditions produce C1-C4 oxygenated hydrocarbons including acetaldehyde, methanol, and short-chain alcohols. The combination of CO, H2, and formaldehyde on magnetite surfaces extends the C1\u2192C2 chain-growth step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly acidic conditions pH 4-6 accelerate decarboxylation; wet-dry cycles concentrate pyruvate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes beta-keto acid decarboxylation at the alpha-carbon, losing CO2 and forming acetaldehyde. The montmorillonite surface stabilizes the transition state through Lewis acid interactions of interlayer cations (Fe3+, Al3+) with the carbonyl oxygen. Protonation of the enolate intermediate yields acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate is well-documented and proceeds readily at modest temperatures. Novikov & Copley (2013, Origins Life Evol. Biosphere) demonstrated pyruvate decarboxylation under prebiotic conditions. Clay minerals catalyze this reaction through Lewis acid activation (Bernal, 1951). This reaction provides a feedback loop from pyruvate to acetaldehyde, creating bidirectional connectivity between these hub molecules.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Carbonylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate on FeNiS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/NiS mixed sulfide surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO from vent fluids; analogous to acetyl-CoA pathway carbon monoxide dehydrogenase chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde adsorbs on the FeNiS surface through its carbonyl oxygen. CO coordinates to a Ni site and inserts into the surface-bound acetaldehyde C-H bond at the methyl position, forming a surface-bound pyruvaldehyde intermediate. Hydration and oxidation of the terminal aldehyde to carboxylate yields pyruvate. Alternatively, CO inserts directly into the Fe-CH(OH)CH3 bond followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, Science) demonstrated that CO in the presence of FeS/NiS catalysts promotes carbonylation reactions analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. Cody et al. (2000, Science) showed pyruvate formation from CO and simple organics on FeS at 250\u00b0C and 2000 bar. The carbonylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate is the microscopic reverse of decarboxylation (rxn_005), establishing a thermodynamic equilibrium controlled by CO partial pressure.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO2 reduction to pyruvate on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (30-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe0) with awaruite (Ni3Fe) and chromite (FeCr2O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Requires sustained reducing conditions; Fe0 oxidation provides driving force\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multiple sequential reduction and C-C coupling steps on the Fe0 surface: CO2 is first reduced to CO or formate, then undergoes surface-mediated C-C coupling to form C2 (acetaldehyde/glycolaldehyde) and C3 (pyruvate) products. The Fe0/Ni surface facilitates carbonyl insertion and C-C bond formation through organometallic intermediates. Pyruvate accumulates as a kinetically stable product due to its chelation stability on the mineral surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated direct formation of pyruvate from CO2 and H2 on native iron under mild hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, 25 bar). Yields of pyruvate were significant among C3 products. The reaction proceeds through implicit C1 and C2 intermediates on the surface, but pyruvate is the released product. This provides a shortcut pathway that bypasses the need for explicit formaldehyde and acetaldehyde intermediates in solution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"rTCA analog step; requires CO2 activation on mineral surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate adsorbs on the greigite surface through its alpha-keto group. CO2 is activated on an adjacent Fe site. Nucleophilic addition of the surface-activated CO2 to the pyruvate enolate forms a C4 beta-keto diacid (oxaloacetate). The reaction is analogous to the pyruvate carboxylase step of the reductive TCA cycle but driven by the mineral surface redox chemistry rather than ATP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that Fe0/FeS systems promote reductive carboxylation reactions analogous to rTCA cycle steps. Springsteen et al. (2018) showed that alpha-keto acids undergo facile carboxylation in the presence of Fe2+ and sulfide. The pyruvate\u2192oxaloacetate step is the first of three consecutive rTCA analog reactions (rxn_008, rxn_009, rxn_010) that build the C5 alpha-ketoglutarate scaffold.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive conversion of oxaloacetate to succinate via rTCA segment\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4) and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Multi-step: OAA \u2192 malate \u2192 fumarate \u2192 succinate; all reductive steps driven by H2 on mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"This represents three consecutive rTCA analog reactions on the greigite/magnetite surface: (1) Reduction of the OAA keto group by surface hydride to give malate; (2) Dehydration of malate to fumarate, catalyzed by Lewis acid sites on the mineral; (3) Reduction of the fumarate C=C double bond by H2 to yield succinate. All three reactions are thermodynamically favorable under reducing hydrothermal conditions and proceed on the same mineral surface without intermediate release.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated the complete OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate reduction sequence using Fe0 as reductant at 70\u00b0C in aqueous solution. Varma et al. (2018) also observed succinate production from CO2 on native iron. Keller et al. (2014, PLOS ONE) showed similar reductive transformations in the presence of FeS at elevated temperatures. The three-step sequence is grouped as a single reaction node because the intermediates (malate, fumarate) remain surface-bound and are not released in significant quantities.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4) with FeS2 co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Analogous to the succinyl-CoA \u2192 alpha-ketoglutarate step of rTCA; requires CO2 fixation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Succinate is activated on the greigite surface through coordination of both carboxylates to Fe centers, forming a chelated surface species. CO2 inserts into the activated C-H bond alpha to one carboxylate, generating a C5 tricarboxylate intermediate. Oxidation at the alpha position yields the alpha-keto functionality of alpha-ketoglutarate. The mineral surface provides both the CO2 activation and the regioselectivity for carboxylation at the correct position.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The conversion of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate is the key C4\u2192C5 chain extension in the rTCA cycle. Muchowska et al. (2017) observed formation of alpha-ketoglutarate from succinate in their iron-driven rTCA analog network, though yields were lower than for the upstream steps. Keller et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) confirmed that FeS minerals promote this carboxylation under hydrothermal conditions. This step completes the C3\u2192C5 build-up through explicit C4 intermediates (OAA, succinate), addressing the oversimplification concern from prior attempts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH3 from vent fluids (geological ammonia); pH 8-10 favors imine formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks the alpha-keto carbonyl of alpha-ketoglutarate to form a carbinolamine intermediate, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base). Reduction of the imine C=N bond by mineral-surface hydrogen (from H2 dissociation on FeS) yields glutamate. The reaction is analogous to biological glutamate dehydrogenase but uses mineral-derived reducing equivalents instead of NAD(P)H.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on FeS surfaces is well-supported. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Lett.) demonstrated reductive amination of alpha-keto acids including pyruvate and oxaloacetate under hydrothermal conditions with FeS. Wang et al. (2005) showed similar transformations with NH3 and H2 on FeS at 100\u00b0C. The alkaline pH of hydrothermal vent fluids (pH 9-11) favors the nucleophilic addition of NH3 to the ketone carbonyl.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-photocatalytic reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 anatase nanoparticles\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-350 nm, no ozone shield); anoxic conditions prevent re-oxidation; glutamate adsorbed on TiO2 via alpha-amino-carboxylate chelation exposing gamma-carboxyl\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"TiO2 absorbs UV light generating electron-hole pairs. Glutamate adsorbs onto TiO2 through its alpha-amino acid moiety (bidentate chelation of -NH2 and alpha-COO- to Ti4+ surface sites), orienting the gamma-carboxyl away from the surface and toward the solution/UV interface. Photogenerated electrons reduce the gamma-carboxyl through a two-electron process: -COOH + 2H+ + 2e- \u2192 -CHO + H2O. Selectivity arises from the surface-protection of the alpha-carboxyl (bound to TiO2) while the distal gamma-carboxyl is exposed to photoreduction. Co-catalyst stibnite provides hole-scavenging to prevent back-oxidation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis is well-established for selective organic transformations. Kisch (2015, Semiconductor Photocatalysis) documented selective photocatalytic reduction of carboxylic acids to aldehydes on TiO2 in the presence of hole scavengers. The regioselectivity for gamma-carboxyl reduction over alpha-carboxyl reduction is justified by the preferential bidentate binding of the alpha-amino acid head group to TiO2, which electronically protects the alpha-carboxyl. This is the most speculative step in the rTCA-glutamate pathway but is significantly more defensible than thermal carboxyl reduction, which was correctly identified as problematic in prior attempts. Early Earth's intense UV radiation (no ozone layer) provides ample photonic driving force.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to ornithine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"struvite (MgNH4PO4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite interlayer Fe3+/Fe2+ redox pair\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline conditions pH 8-9; NH3 concentration enriched by wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH3 attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to form a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base). The montmorillonite interlayer Fe2+/Fe3+ redox couple provides the reducing equivalents for imine reduction: Fe2+ \u2192 Fe3+ + e-. Two electrons reduce the C=N bond to C-NH2, yielding ornithine. The clay surface concentrates both substrates through ion exchange and surface adsorption.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of aldehydes by NH3 is a fundamental prebiotic reaction. Barge et al. (2019) showed that Fe-bearing minerals can drive reductive amination under ambient conditions. Montmorillonite clays concentrate amino compounds and aldehydes in their interlayers (Ferris, 2005, Elements), providing both the catalytic surface and the concentration mechanism. The structural iron in montmorillonite (Fe2+/Fe3+) has been shown to participate in redox chemistry (Stucki et al., 2002, Applied Clay Science). This step completes the rTCA-glutamate branch pathway to ornithine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"UV radical coupling of acetaldehyde to succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 anatase as photosensitizer\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-320 nm); anoxic atmosphere; requires sufficient acetaldehyde concentration from wet-dry enrichment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photolysis of acetaldehyde generates alpha-carbon radicals through Norrish Type II hydrogen abstraction: CH3CHO + hv \u2192 \u2022CH2CHO + H\u2022. TiO2 photocatalysis also generates \u2022CH2CHO radicals through surface hole-mediated H-abstraction. Radical-radical coupling of two \u2022CH2CHO radicals yields succinaldehyde (OHC-CH2-CH2-CHO). The competing Norrish Type I cleavage (CH3\u2022 + \u2022CHO) produces methane and CO as byproducts, but the Type II pathway is favored at longer UV wavelengths (>280 nm) and on TiO2 surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Norrish-type photochemistry of acetaldehyde is extensively documented (Norrish, 1934; Calvert & Pitts, 1966, Photochemistry). The radical coupling of alpha-oxy radicals to form dialdehydes is established in photochemical synthesis. TiO2 photocatalysis enhances radical generation selectivity. On the early Earth, intense UV flux and anoxic conditions would favor radical chemistry. Succinaldehyde has been detected in UV photolysis experiments of acetaldehyde (Back & Yamamoto, 1985, Can. J. Chem.). This provides a completely different C4 intermediate from the rTCA succinate route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective mono-reductive amination of succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (Fe2+/Fe3+ structural iron)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Sub-stoichiometric NH3 to favor mono-amination; dilute conditions with slow NH3 diffusion from vent gases; pH 7-8\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under kinetically controlled conditions with limiting NH3, one aldehyde of succinaldehyde undergoes nucleophilic addition by NH3 to form a mono-carbinolamine. Dehydration gives a mono-imine, which is reduced by Fe2+ in the montmorillonite lattice to give 4-aminobutanal. Selectivity for mono-amination is achieved through: (1) sub-stoichiometric NH3 (statistical preference); (2) the first amination product (4-aminobutanal) is less electrophilic at the remaining aldehyde due to the electron-donating effect of the distal amino group; (3) intramolecular cyclization of the diamine product removes any diamine formed.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Selective mono-functionalization of symmetric dialdehydes is achievable under kinetic control with limiting reagent. The montmorillonite surface provides both the reductive capacity (structural Fe2+) and concentration effects. The selectivity argument is strengthened by the observation that 4-aminobutanal can form a stable cyclic hemiaminal (2-hydroxypyrrolidine) that protects the aldehyde from further amination. This route to 4-aminobutanal avoids the problematic carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction that was correctly identified as a weakness in prior attempts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of ornithine from 4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Two-step process: (1) Strecker aminonitrile formation, (2) hydrolysis; wet-dry cycling drives both concentration and hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: NH3 attacks the aldehyde of 4-aminobutanal to form an imine (Schiff base). HCN adds to the imine C=N bond to give 2-amino-5-aminopentanenitrile (ornithine aminonitrile). Step 2: Hydrolysis of the nitrile group occurs during the wet phase of a wet-dry cycle. The aminonitrile C\u2261N bond is hydrated first to an amide, then to a carboxylic acid, yielding ornithine (2,5-diaminopentanoic acid). Montmorillonite catalyzes both the imine formation (Lewis acid activation) and the nitrile hydrolysis (surface water activation).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the most robust and well-documented prebiotic amino acid syntheses. Miller (1957, Biochim. Biophys. Acta) and subsequent workers showed that Strecker synthesis operates efficiently under prebiotic conditions. The key advantage here is that 4-aminobutanal provides the correct C4 aminoaldehyde substrate to produce the C5 amino acid ornithine in a single well-understood reaction, completely bypassing the need for selective carboxyl reduction. Parker et al. (2011, Origins Life Evol. Biosphere) confirmed Strecker synthesis of various amino acids including diamino acids from appropriate aldehyde precursors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of urea from CO2 and NH3\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite surface concentrates NH3 and CO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Equilibrium favored at high pressure; CO2 and NH3 from vent fluids; proceeds through ammonium carbamate intermediate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 reacts with NH3 to form ammonium carbamate (NH4+[H2NCOO-]) as a kinetically accessible intermediate. At elevated temperature and pressure, ammonium carbamate undergoes intramolecular dehydration to yield urea ((NH2)2CO) and water. The magnetite surface stabilizes the carbamate intermediate through surface coordination and provides a catalytic surface for the dehydration step. This is the industrial Bosch-Meiser process under prebiotic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Urea synthesis from CO2 and NH3 under hydrothermal conditions is thermodynamically favorable at high pressures. Yamagata et al. (1995, Origins Life Evol. Biosphere) demonstrated urea formation from ammonium bicarbonate solutions at 150\u00b0C. Kitadai & Maruyama (2018, Geoscience Frontiers) reviewed the formation of urea under hydrothermal conditions. The ammonium carbamate pathway is the established mechanism for industrial urea synthesis (Bosch-Meiser process) and operates under conditions closely matching alkaline hydrothermal vents.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photohydration of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm); pH 6-8; HCN concentration enriched in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes photocatalytic hydration on TiO2 surfaces. TiO2-generated hydroxyl radicals (\u2022OH from water oxidation by holes) or surface-activated water molecules attack the HCN carbon. The resulting iminol tautomerizes to formamide (HCONH2). Direct UV photolysis of HCN in water also produces formamide through a similar radical mechanism. TiO2 enhances yields by providing a surface for adsorption and radical generation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN hydration to formamide is a well-established reaction under both thermal and photochemical conditions. Saladino et al. (2012, Chem. Soc. Rev.) extensively documented formamide as a central prebiotic molecule formed from HCN hydration. Barks et al. (2010, ChemBioChem) showed UV-enhanced formamide formation from HCN in water. Formamide serves as an alternative entry point to urea (rxn_019), providing a second convergent route to the cyanamide precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal conversion of formamide to urea via isocyanic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Dry phase of wet-dry cycle; formamide concentrated by evaporation; thermal dehydration drives equilibrium\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"During the dry phase of a wet-dry cycle, concentrated formamide undergoes thermal dehydration to isocyanic acid (HNCO): HCONH2 \u2192 HNCO + H2O. Isocyanic acid is a reactive electrophile that immediately attacks available NH3 nucleophile: HNCO + NH3 \u2192 (NH2)2CO (urea). This is the W\u00f6hler synthesis. The montmorillonite surface concentrates formamide through adsorption, and apatite provides phosphate that can catalyze the dehydration. The reaction proceeds efficiently at 80-100\u00b0C during the evaporative/dry phase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide thermal chemistry is extensively documented by Saladino et al. (2004, 2012). Thermal decomposition of formamide yields HNCO among other products. The W\u00f6hler synthesis (HNCO + NH3 \u2192 urea) is one of the most fundamental reactions in organic chemistry (W\u00f6hler, 1828). \u0160poner et al. (2016, Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys.) showed that formamide on mineral surfaces undergoes selective thermal transformations. This route provides a second pathway to urea from HCN-derived formamide, creating convergence at the urea hub.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal dehydration of urea to cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-410K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and struvite co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Dry phase at elevated temperature; geothermal heating; cyanamide stabilized by rapid dissolution in next wet phase\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Urea undergoes thermal elimination of water to produce cyanamide (H2NCN): (NH2)2CO \u2192 H2NCN + H2O. The reaction proceeds through an isourea intermediate. At temperatures above 130\u00b0C (403K), the dehydration is thermodynamically favorable. The montmorillonite surface catalyzes the dehydration through Lewis acid activation of the carbonyl oxygen. Struvite (MgNH4PO4) may provide phosphate-mediated activation of the urea carbonyl, lowering the activation barrier. Cyanamide is kinetically stable once formed and dissolves in the next wet phase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decomposition of urea to cyanamide is a well-established reaction in industrial chemistry (Buchner, 1995, Industrial Inorganic Chemistry). Schaber et al. (2004, Thermochimica Acta) characterized the thermal decomposition products of urea, confirming cyanamide as a primary product at 130-200\u00b0C. Under prebiotic geothermal conditions, surface temperatures of 100-150\u00b0C are readily accessible. Danger et al. (2013, Chem. Soc. Rev.) noted cyanamide as a plausible prebiotic condensing agent available from urea decomposition. This is the most well-supported cyanamide formation pathway, addressing the concern about uncertain HCN+NH3+UV routes in prior attempts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide to form arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10 optimal for delta-amino nucleophilicity; prebiotic pool conditions; wet phase\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The delta-amino group of ornithine (-CH2NH2) acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). The initial adduct is an N-cyanoornithine intermediate, which tautomerizes and picks up a proton to yield the guanidinium group. The reaction proceeds through: (1) nucleophilic addition of ornithine delta-NH2 to cyanamide C\u2261N; (2) proton transfer to give an amidine; (3) tautomerization to the thermodynamically stable guanidinium form of arginine. No catalyst required; the reaction proceeds spontaneously at mildly alkaline pH.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanamide reacts with amines to form guanidines under mild aqueous conditions \u2014 this is a textbook reaction in organic chemistry. Steinman et al. (1964, Archives of Biochemistry and Biophysics) demonstrated the formation of guanidine and substituted guanidines from cyanamide and amines under prebiotic conditions. Danger et al. (2013, Chem. Soc. Rev.) identified cyanamide as a key prebiotic reagent for guanidinium installation. The delta-amino group of ornithine is a primary amine with a pKa ~10.5, making it a competent nucleophile at slightly alkaline pH (8-10). This step is the most prebiotically defensible route to the arginine guanidinium group, as identified in the feedback from prior attempts.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full rTCA-Glutamate Pathway via Formate\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete hydrothermal carbon fixation from CO2 through formate and formaldehyde to acetaldehyde, then carbonylation to pyruvate, rTCA elaboration to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, surface photocatalytic reduction to semialdehyde, reductive amination to ornithine, combined with hydrothermal urea synthesis and surface cyanamide formation for final guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Formaldehyde rTCA-Glutamate Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Bypasses formate by using direct CO2-to-formaldehyde reduction on native iron, then proceeds through the same FTT, carbonylation, rTCA, and glutamate branch to ornithine. Uses hydrothermal urea for cyanamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Pyruvate rTCA-Glutamate Pathway (Shortest rTCA Route)\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses direct CO2-to-pyruvate reduction on native iron (Varma et al., 2018), bypassing all C1 and C2 intermediates in solution. Proceeds through rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, and ornithine. Minimizes total reaction steps. Uses hydrothermal urea for cyanamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde-Strecker Pathway via Formate\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C1 fixation through formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192acetaldehyde, then surface UV radical coupling to succinaldehyde, selective mono-reductive amination to 4-aminobutanal, and Strecker synthesis of ornithine. This entirely bypasses the problematic glutamate-5-semialdehyde route. Uses hydrothermal urea for cyanamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde-Strecker Pathway via Direct Formaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses direct CO2-to-formaldehyde on native iron, then FTT to acetaldehyde, UV radical coupling to succinaldehyde, and Strecker ornithine synthesis. Bypasses both formate and the glutamate branch. Uses hydrothermal urea for cyanamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde-Strecker via Pyruvate Decarboxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses direct CO2-to-pyruvate on native iron, then surface thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, UV radical coupling to succinaldehyde, and Strecker ornithine synthesis. Demonstrates bidirectional pyruvate-acetaldehyde connectivity. Uses hydrothermal urea for cyanamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"rTCA-Glutamate with Formamide-Urea Cyanamide Route\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses the direct pyruvate rTCA-glutamate pathway to ornithine, combined with the alternative HCN\u2192formamide\u2192urea\u2192cyanamide pathway for the guanidinium donor. Demonstrates full independence from hydrothermal urea synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde-Strecker with Formamide-Urea Route (via Formate)\",\n      \"description\": \"Combines the formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192acetaldehyde\u2192succinaldehyde-Strecker ornithine branch with the HCN\u2192formamide\u2192urea\u2192cyanamide guanidinium branch. Both branches use surface chemistry for the key transformations.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde-Strecker with Formamide-Urea Route (via Direct HCHO)\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses direct formaldehyde synthesis on native iron, FTT to acetaldehyde, succinaldehyde-Strecker to ornithine, and HCN-formamide-urea route to cyanamide. Maximizes use of surface photochemistry for both branches.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-Decarboxylation Strecker + Formamide-Urea (Minimal Hydrothermal)\",\n      \"description\": \"The most surface-chemistry-dominated pathway: only the initial CO2\u2192pyruvate step is hydrothermal. Pyruvate is decarboxylated on the surface to acetaldehyde, which undergoes UV radical coupling, Strecker synthesis to ornithine, while HCN is photohydrated to formamide, converted to urea, then cyanamide, for final guanidination. Demonstrates maximal environmental utilization of surface photochemistry and wet-dry cycling.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde hub - convergent product of two distinct CO2 reduction pathways (via formate on greigite, and direct on native iron); feeds into FTT acetaldehyde synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 682756.3922405243, "success": false, "error_message": "Unterminated string starting at: line 641 column 30 (char 47381)"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-14T14:37:54.226725", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Arginine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.7\n- Feedback: This is a thoughtfully designed synthesis network for arginine with strong conceptual foundations. The five hub molecules (HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, glutamate, ornithine) are well-chosen and create meaningful convergence points. The overall strategy of building ornithine from glutamate and then installing the guanidinium group via cyanamide is sound and aligns with both biosynthetic logic and known prebiotic chemistry. However, three persistent chemical issues prevent approval: (1) The C1\u2192C3 pyruvate synthesis (rxn_003) and C3\u2192C5 alpha-ketoglutarate synthesis (rxn_004) are oversimplified \u2014 each requires at minimum one additional explicit intermediate. (2) The selective reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to semialdehyde (rxn_007) is the most problematic step \u2014 this is thermodynamically uphill and kinetically demanding without enzymatic activation. Alternative routes to ornithine (e.g., via diaminobutyrate homologation or direct Strecker-type synthesis of ornithine from an appropriate aldehyde) should be explored. (3) The urea/citrulline\u2192arginine conversion (rxn_012) lacks a clear prebiotic mechanism for the final amination step. The cyanamide guanidination route is significantly more defensible. Mineral catalysts are not specified for any reaction, which weakens the environmental grounding. Despite these issues, the network topology and strategic design are strong (0.85), and with refinement of 3-4 key reactions, this network could reach the approval threshold.\n- Issues: ['Strongest environmental progression (H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B). CO2 reduction to formate is well-supported, but pyruvate synthesis from formate+formaldehyde (rxn_003) is a significant chemical leap requiring several implicit intermediates. The C3\u2192C5 reductive carboxylation (rxn_004) also skips oxaloacetate. Most critically, selective reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to semialdehyde (rxn_007) is thermodynamically and kinetically challenging without enzymatic activation. Final guanidination by cyanamide (rxn_011) is well-documented prebiotically.', 'Shares the same problematic early steps as P1. The urea/citrulline route (rxn_012) is weaker than direct cyanamide guanidination because conversion of citrulline to arginine requires an activated nitrogen source (not just NH3). Biochemically this step requires ATP and aspartate; prebiotically the mechanism is unclear. Having citrulline and arginine as co-products in one step is chemically unjustified.', 'Shorter pathway is appealing but rxn_006 (extended Strecker to glutamate) is poorly defined \u2014 building a C5 amino acid from C1 units in a single step requires multiple implicit aldol condensations plus a Strecker reaction. The environmental flow (S\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B) is less clean than P1. The glutamate-to-ornithine conversion (rxn_007, rxn_008) remains the weak link.', 'Combines the weaknesses of P3 (extended Strecker) with the problematic urea/citrulline route. Least viable of the main pathways. Environmental progression is also mixed.', 'Very similar to P1, emphasizing formate as the sole CO2 reduction product. Avoids the need for FTT formaldehyde (rxn_002) but still requires formaldehyde for rxn_003. Essentially this pathway needs better definition of how formaldehyde enters if not through rxn_002.', 'Formaldehyde as the central hub feeding into Strecker chemistry is conceptually elegant. However, rxn_006 remains the bottleneck \u2014 building glutamate from formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 in one step is a major oversimplification. The H\u2192S\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B flow is acceptable.', 'HCN serving as both the carbon backbone source (Strecker) and guanidinium donor (cyanamide) is a strong conceptual framework. The dual-use of HCN is prebiotically elegant. However, chemical execution issues in rxn_006 and rxn_007 lower the score. The most conceptually unified pathway.', 'HCN-centric variant using the weaker urea/citrulline route. Combines the Strecker oversimplification with the problematic rxn_012. Less viable than P7.', 'Best mixed-environment pathway. Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces alpha-ketoglutarate, then surface amination and guanidination complete the synthesis. Notably bypasses the problematic glutamate\u2192semialdehyde reduction (rxn_007) if surface amination is performed differently. However, the pathway description suggests it still passes through ornithine, so rxn_007/rxn_008 may still be needed. The best environmental flow among all pathways.', \"The dual-convergent pathway leverages redundancy from both hydrothermal and Strecker routes to glutamate, and both guanidination pathways. While maximizing network robustness, it inherits all the chemical weaknesses of the component pathways. The redundancy concept is sound for prebiotic plausibility arguments but doesn't improve the chemical feasibility of the weakest steps.\"]\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: This is a well-architected synthesis network for arginine that demonstrates genuine strategic improvements over naive approaches: the glutamate\u2192GABA\u21924-aminobutanal route avoids direct gamma-carboxyl reduction selectivity issues, and the cyanamide guanidination is the correct prebiotic approach. The network has strong topology with 18 molecules, 16 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points creating meaningful redundancy. The rTCA chemistry core (rxn_003, 006-008, 010) is well-supported by literature. Two critical bottlenecks persist across ALL pathways and cannot be circumvented within the current network architecture: (1) rxn_013 \u2014 the carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction of GABA on mackinawite lacks strong experimental precedent for selective partial reduction stopping at the aldehyde, and (2) rxn_015 \u2014 cyanamide formation from HCN + NH3 under UV is mechanistically uncertain (photochemistry of HCN more commonly yields oligomeric products or formamide rather than cyanamide). Since every pathway to arginine must traverse both rxn_013 and rxn_015, these are network-level vulnerabilities. Addressing either one \u2014 e.g., by providing an alternative ornithine source that bypasses 4-aminobutanal, or an alternative guanidinium donor with better-documented formation \u2014 would push the network above the approval threshold. The best pathway P6 achieves borderline approval at 0.80 by minimizing additional weak steps.\n- Issues: ['Longest pathway with the most reaction steps; includes the weak formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_002) and the thermodynamically problematic GABA carboxyl reduction (rxn_013). Multiple hydrothermal-surface transitions weaken the environmental narrative. The chain of 13 steps means cumulative yield issues are significant.', 'Eliminates the weak formate\u2192formaldehyde step by using direct CO2\u2192pyruvate on native iron. Cleaner environmental flow with a long hydrothermal block followed by surface chemistry and biochemical finish. Still bottlenecked by rxn_013 (GABA reduction) and rxn_015 (cyanamide formation).', 'Combines the weakest elements: formate\u2192formaldehyde (rxn_002), succinate\u2192succinic semialdehyde (rxn_009), and GABA reduction (rxn_013). Three separate carboxyl/carbonyl reduction bottlenecks make this the least chemically robust route. The Strecker synthesis of glutamate from succinic semialdehyde (rxn_011) is itself sound, but producing the aldehyde substrate is the problem.', 'Hybrid route using direct pyruvate synthesis and Strecker glutamate. Still suffers from succinate\u2192succinic semialdehyde (rxn_009) and GABA reduction (rxn_013). Two separate difficult carboxyl reductions lower confidence.', 'Formaldehyde-centric buildup showcases the C1\u2192C2\u2192C3\u2192C5 logic well. Includes the formate reduction step which is moderate risk. Same terminal bottlenecks as other pathways (rxn_013, rxn_015).', \"Dual-HCN route using Strecker chemistry twice. Elegant in concept but doubles down on the difficult succinate\u2192succinic semialdehyde reduction. The dual use of HCN is a nice thematic element but doesn't solve the thermodynamic bottlenecks.\", 'Longest formate-based route combined with the Strecker glutamate branch. Accumulates the most problematic steps (rxn_002, rxn_009, rxn_013, rxn_015). Too many weak links for high confidence.', 'Succinate branching pathway demonstrates network redundancy by exploring both branches from the succinate hub. Useful for showing convergence but inherits the weaknesses of both branches simultaneously.', 'Explicitly designed to showcase the Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical environmental cycle. Best environmental narrative among all pathways. The back-and-forth is justified by the chemistry: C1 fixation (hydrothermal), aldol (surface), carbonylation+rTCA (hydrothermal), decarboxylation+Strecker (surface), guanidination (biochemical). Still limited by the same terminal bottlenecks.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Arginine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network builds arginine through a multi-environment strategy with five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, ornithine). The key innovations addressing prior criticisms: (1) Ornithine is produced via a phosphorylation-assisted reduction of glutamate, where glutamyl-5-phosphate is formed on apatite under dry heat, then the activated acyl-phosphate is reduced on mackinawite/Fe\u2070 to glutamate-5-semialdehyde \u2014 this avoids the thermodynamically forbidden direct carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction. (2) Cyanamide is generated via well-documented thermal dehydration of urea (itself from ammonium cyanate rearrangement), avoiding the problematic HCN+NH3+UV route. (3) Pyruvate synthesis uses two documented routes: direct CO2 reduction on native iron (Varma et al., 2018) and stepwise C1 buildup through formate/formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde. (4) The rTCA partial cycle to alpha-ketoglutarate proceeds through explicit oxaloacetate and succinate intermediates with individual mineral catalysts specified. (5) An alternative Strecker route to glutamate bypasses the full rTCA by using succinic semialdehyde derived from decarboxylation of alpha-ketoglutarate. Ten pathways arise from combinatorial selection across two pyruvate routes, two alpha-ketoglutarate routes, two glutamate routes, and two cyanamide precursor routes, all converging through the ornithine hub.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"Ca5(PO4)3(OH)\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydroxylapatite\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Apatite / Inorganic phosphate source\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4-6)1-3(7)8/h1H2,(H,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Succinate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10NO7P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-phospho-L-glutamate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Glutamyl-5-phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-5-7)8-9/h5H,1-3,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ornithine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Urea\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Cyanamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H14N4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-2-amino-5-guanidinopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Arginine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-oxobutanoic acid, 2-amino-\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH4OCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonium cyanate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ammonium cyanate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is adsorbed on Fe3S4 surface, where it undergoes a two-electron reduction by H2 to produce formate (HCOO\u207b). The greigite surface mimics the active site of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase. H2 dissociates on the FeS surface, providing hydride equivalents for CO2 reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Demonstrated experimentally by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) who showed CO2 reduction to formate on native iron and iron-nickel-sulfide precipitates under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions. Roldan et al. (2015, Chemical Communications) showed greigite specifically catalyzes CO2 reduction to formate at ambient temperature under alkaline conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO2 reduction to pyruvate on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>30 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe0, awaruite Fe3Ni) with magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH, CO2 saturated\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Native iron (Fe0) serves as a strong reductant, donating electrons to CO2. The reaction proceeds through multiple C-C bond forming steps on the iron surface: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO/formyl species \u2192 acetaldehyde/acetate \u2192 pyruvate. The iron surface provides both reducing power and a template for C-C bond formation via radical recombination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron (Fe0) reduces CO2 to pyruvate, acetate, and other organic acids under hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, moderate pressures). Yields of pyruvate were significant. This represents a single-step fixation pathway from CO2 to a C3 alpha-keto acid, bypassing the need for stepwise C1 buildup. The native iron acts as both electron donor and surface catalyst.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite with trace native iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Strongly reducing conditions, H2 excess\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbed on the magnetite surface undergoes partial reduction by H2. The Fe(II)/Fe(III) redox couple in magnetite mediates electron transfer. The O-H bond of formate is cleaved and the resulting formyl intermediate is protonated to yield formaldehyde. Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) chemistry on magnetite surfaces produces formaldehyde as a kinetic intermediate before further reduction to methanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom & Seewald (2003, Earth and Planetary Science Letters) demonstrated FTT synthesis on magnetite producing aldehydes and alcohols. He et al. (2019, ACS Central Science) showed that formaldehyde can be generated from CO/CO2 reduction under hydrothermal conditions. Formaldehyde is kinetically trapped at moderate temperatures before further reduction to methanol occurs. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under strongly reducing conditions with excess H2.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde aldol condensation to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay with Ca(OH)2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 10-12, Ca2+ ions present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. Ca(OH)2 generates the enolizable species (Cannizzaro disproportionation provides formate + methanol, while the enolized formaldehyde attacks a second formaldehyde molecule). Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate formaldehyde and stabilize the glycolaldehyde product through adsorption, preventing further condensation to higher sugars.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the first step of the formose reaction, well-documented by Breslow (1959). Weber (2001, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) showed that glycolaldehyde forms preferentially as the initial C2 product. Borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde, but at the clay surface the concentration effect prevents runaway polymerization (Scorei, 2012). Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) showed borate stabilization of sugars in formose-like systems.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Stepwise pyruvate synthesis from glycolaldehyde and CO via carbonylation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>20 bar CO/CO2)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, iron-nickel sulfide surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO/CO2/H2 mixed gas phase, alkaline vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde is oxidized to glyoxylate at the FeS2 surface. Glyoxylate then undergoes reductive carboxylation with CO2/CO on the Fe3S4 surface, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. CO binds to the iron-sulfur surface, forming a metal-carbonyl intermediate, which inserts into the C-H bond of glyoxylate to form pyruvate. Alternatively, glyoxylate condenses with formaldehyde and is then oxidized to pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cody et al. (2000, Science) demonstrated pyruvate formation from C1-C2 precursors under hydrothermal conditions on FeS surfaces. Huber & Wachtershauser (1997, Science) showed carbonylation reactions on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces producing activated acyl species. The glycolaldehyde-to-pyruvate conversion through glyoxylate is consistent with the iron-sulfur world hypothesis and provides an explicit C2\u2192C3 buildup pathway with defined intermediates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate (rTCA step)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe3S4 / FeS with Cr(III) or Zn(II) cofactors\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO2-rich alkaline fluids, reducing environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is activated on the greigite surface and inserts into the C2-H bond of pyruvate via a carboxylation mechanism analogous to pyruvate carboxylase. The mineral surface stabilizes the enolpyruvate tautomer, facilitating nucleophilic attack on the electrophilic carbon of surface-bound CO2. This is the reverse of the oxidative decarboxylation of oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that iron(0) promotes non-enzymatic analogs of TCA cycle reactions including the reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate. Varma et al. (2018) and Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed that Fe0/FeS promotes a network of rTCA reactions. Keller et al. (2014, Molecular Systems Biology) showed non-enzymatic rTCA-like reactions under volcanic aqueous conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of oxaloacetate to succinate via malate and fumarate (rTCA segment)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 with Fe3O4\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions, H2 from serpentinization, intermediates: malate, fumarate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three-step reduction sequence: (1) Oxaloacetate is reduced to malate by H2 on Fe0 surface (keto reduction). (2) Malate dehydrates to fumarate on the mineral surface (elimination, thermally driven). (3) Fumarate is reduced to succinate by H2 on Fe0 (C=C reduction). These are individually documented steps of the reductive TCA cycle. The Fe0/magnetite surface catalyzes all three transformations.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated the complete non-enzymatic promotion of the reductive TCA cycle by metallic iron (Fe0) in water at 70-100\u00b0C. All three steps (OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate) were observed with high yields. The reduction steps are thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions at hydrothermal vents where serpentinization generates abundant H2. Presented as a combined reaction node for network clarity, but proceeds through explicit malate and fumarate intermediates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>20 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 with Fe3S4\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO2-saturated reducing solution, Zn2+ as possible cofactor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Succinate is activated at one carboxyl terminus on the Fe3S4 surface. CO2 inserts via a radical or anionic mechanism to form the C5 skeleton of alpha-ketoglutarate. The FeS surface provides reducing equivalents to drive the thermodynamically uphill carboxylation through coupling to Fe0 oxidation. The reaction may proceed through succinyl-thioester intermediate on the sulfide surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed this reaction occurring as part of the non-enzymatic rTCA network on Fe0. The reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate is the key C4\u2192C5 chain extension of the rTCA cycle. Yield is lower than the OAA\u2192succinate steps but is detectible. Camprubi et al. (2019) proposed that the alkaline vent pH gradient provides additional thermodynamic driving force for this endergonic step. This is the most thermodynamically challenging step in the rTCA analog.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS with Fe0 as reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH4+ from hydrothermal fluids, pH 6-9, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks the C2 keto group of alpha-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base). The imine is reduced by H2 (or surface-bound hydride on FeS) to yield glutamate. The FeS surface both catalyzes imine formation through Lewis acid activation of the ketone and provides reducing equivalents for imine reduction. This is a reductive amination, one of the most fundamental prebiotic amino acid forming reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) showed reductive amination of alpha-keto acids (including pyruvate to alanine) under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions using iron oxyhydroxide minerals. Wang et al. (2011) demonstrated similar reactions on FeS surfaces. Huber & Wachtershauser (2006) showed amino acid formation from alpha-keto acids and NH3 under volcanic conditions. The reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate is the most direct and thermodynamically favorable route to this amino acid.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidative decarboxylation of alpha-ketoglutarate to succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, aerobic-free but UV-driven oxidative decarboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate undergoes UV-photocatalyzed oxidative decarboxylation at C1-C2, losing CO2 and generating succinic semialdehyde (4-oxobutanoic acid). TiO2 generates reactive oxygen species under UV that abstract an electron from the alpha-keto group, facilitating decarboxylation. This is a thermodynamically favorable (exergonic) reaction driven by both UV energy and the stability of CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Oxidative decarboxylation of alpha-keto acids is thermodynamically spontaneous (\u0394G < 0) and occurs readily under UV irradiation. Rapf & Vaida (2016) documented photodegradation of alpha-keto acids including pyruvate under UV conditions relevant to early Earth. Alpha-ketoglutarate decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde is well-known in biochemistry and occurs non-enzymatically under oxidative or UV conditions. TiO2 photocatalysis of organic acid transformations is documented by Shkrob et al. (2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of glutamate from succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool conditions, concentrated HCN and NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis: (1) Ammonia attacks the aldehyde of succinic semialdehyde to form an amino alcohol, then dehydrates to an imine. (2) HCN adds to the imine to form an alpha-aminonitrile (2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid is not formed; rather 2-amino-5-cyanopentanenitrile \u2014 correction: the Strecker adds HCN to give alpha-amino nitrile at the aldehyde carbon). (3) The nitrile is hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid (amide intermediate). Product is 2-aminopentanedioic acid = glutamic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the best-documented prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Miller, 1953; Miller & Urey, 1959). The use of succinic semialdehyde (an aliphatic aldehyde with a pendant carboxyl group) as the substrate is a straightforward extension of Strecker chemistry to produce glutamate. Parker et al. (2011, Origins of Life) confirmed Strecker synthesis produces amino acids corresponding to the aldehyde substrate. This provides an alternative surface-chemistry route to glutamate that bypasses hydrothermal reductive amination.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphorylation of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to glutamyl-5-phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"struvite (MgNH4PO4\u00b76H2O) or apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Dry-heat conditions during evaporitic cycle, 60-85\u00b0C, low water activity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"During the drying phase of a wet-dry cycle, glutamate and phosphate minerals are concentrated. At elevated temperature and low water activity, the gamma-carboxyl group of glutamate attacks the phosphorus of the mineral phosphate, forming a mixed anhydride (acyl phosphate) bond. The gamma-carboxyl is selectively phosphorylated over the alpha-carboxyl because it is less sterically hindered and not involved in intramolecular hydrogen bonding with the alpha-amino group. Struvite dissolves to provide reactive phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pasek et al. (2017, Angewandte Chemie) demonstrated phosphorylation of organic acids by reactive phosphorus minerals under mild heating. Burcar et al. (2016) showed dry-state phosphorylation of amino acids and organic acids on mineral surfaces. The formation of acyl phosphates from carboxylic acids and phosphate is well-documented under dehydrating conditions (Gibard et al., 2018, Nature Chemistry). The mixed anhydride (acyl phosphate) is the key activated intermediate that makes subsequent reduction feasible.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive dephosphorylation of glutamyl-5-phosphate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/Fe0 as reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Return to hydrothermal reducing conditions, H2-rich fluids, phosphate released and recycled\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The acyl phosphate bond of glutamyl-5-phosphate is a high-energy mixed anhydride (\u0394G\u00b0hydrolysis ~ -43 kJ/mol), making it thermodynamically activated for reduction. Fe0 or FeS donates two electrons to the acyl-phosphate carbon: the C-O(P) bond is cleaved, phosphate departs as a leaving group, and the carbonyl is reduced to the aldehyde oxidation state. This is analogous to the biological glutamate-5-phosphate reductase reaction but using mineral-surface electrons instead of NADPH. The acyl phosphate activation is the critical innovation: direct carboxyl reduction (\u0394G > +30 kJ/mol) is thermodynamically forbidden, but acyl phosphate reduction (\u0394G ~ -10 kJ/mol) is favorable.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This phosphorylation-assisted reduction strategy mirrors the biological pathway (glutamate kinase \u2192 glutamate-5-phosphate reductase) and is the key solution to the problematic direct carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction identified in previous attempts. Acyl phosphates are well-known activated carboxylic acid derivatives with reduction potentials approximately 400 mV more positive than free carboxylates (Pasek & Kee, 2011). Mullen & Sutherland (2007) discussed acyl phosphate intermediates in prebiotic context. The use of Fe0 as a two-electron reductant for activated substrates is consistent with Muchowska et al. (2019). The phosphate is released and recycled, consistent with catalytic phosphate cycling in prebiotic environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to ornithine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (spontaneous in NH3-rich solution), or pyridoxal as catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Concentrated prebiotic pool, NH4+ at mM-M concentrations, mildly alkaline pH 8-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia (or ammonium ion) attacks the aldehyde carbon of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to form a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to give an imine (Schiff base). The imine is reduced to the amine: in prebiotic conditions, reduction can occur via (1) borohydride-like minerals, (2) transamination with another amino acid (e.g., alanine acting as amino donor), or (3) disproportionation where a second aldehyde molecule acts as hydride donor (Leuckart-Wallach type). Product is L-ornithine (2,5-diaminopentanoic acid).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of aldehydes is one of the most facile prebiotic reactions. Glutamate-5-semialdehyde spontaneously cyclizes to \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate in aqueous solution, but in the presence of excess ammonia, the open-chain form is trapped as the imine and reduced to ornithine. This is documented in biochemistry as the ornithine aminotransferase reaction. Prebiotically, transamination with other amino acids (Wachtershauser, 2000) or reduction by thiols/FeS (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006) can drive the reaction. High ammonia concentrations in early Earth environments (Summers & Chang, 1993) favor the intermolecular amination product over cyclization.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonium cyanate formation from HCN hydrolysis and NH3\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface for concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 8-10\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes base-catalyzed hydrolysis in alkaline solution: HCN + H2O \u2192 HOCN (cyanic acid/isocyanic acid). In the presence of ammonia, isocyanic acid is immediately trapped as ammonium cyanate (NH4OCN). The clay surface concentrates both HCN and NH3 and provides an alkaline microenvironment that favors hydrolysis over oligomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN hydrolysis to cyanate is well-documented in alkaline aqueous solution (Sanchez et al., 1967). The conversion of HCN to HNCO (isocyanic acid) and then to ammonium cyanate in ammonia-containing solutions is a standard aqueous chemistry reaction. Miyakawa et al. (2002) documented cyanate as a major product of HCN processing in prebiotic ocean simulants.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"W\u00f6hler synthesis: ammonium cyanate rearrangement to urea\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"thermal, clay surface assists concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool, heating during dry phase of wet-dry cycle\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonium cyanate undergoes the classic W\u00f6hler rearrangement: NH4+ attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanate (OCN\u207b) intramolecularly, forming urea (H2N-CO-NH2). This is one of the oldest known organic reactions (W\u00f6hler, 1828). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds spontaneously at moderate temperatures. Concentration during evaporitic drying accelerates the reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The W\u00f6hler synthesis (1828) is the original demonstration of abiotic organic synthesis: ammonium cyanate \u2192 urea. This reaction is spontaneous and well-characterized kinetically (Shaw & Bordeaux, 1955). In prebiotic context, Menor-Salvan et al. (2009) showed urea formation from HCN-derived cyanate in simulated early Earth conditions. Urea is detected in Miller-Urey-type experiments and is a plausible prebiotic molecule.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal dehydration of urea to cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface, dry heat\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, volcanic hot spring margins, 80-130\u00b0C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Urea undergoes thermal dehydration: the O-H bond of the enol tautomer breaks, and the C=O is converted to C=NH with loss of water, yielding cyanamide (H2N-CN). This proceeds at temperatures above ~80\u00b0C under dry conditions. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the reaction by stabilizing the transition state through surface interactions. An alternative pathway involves initial isomerization to carbodiimide (HN=C=NH) followed by tautomerization to cyanamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Schimpl et al. (1965) and Lohrmann & Orgel (1968) documented thermal decomposition of urea to cyanamide under dry-heating conditions at 80-130\u00b0C. Gabel & Ponnamperuma (1967) showed urea decomposition products include cyanamide and biuret. This is a well-established thermal reaction. Cyanamide is a key prebiotic condensing agent and guanidinium donor, documented extensively by Orgel and colleagues. The generation of cyanamide from urea via thermal dehydration is a robust, well-characterized prebiotic reaction with no significant mechanistic ambiguity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide to form arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Concentrated prebiotic pool, pH 7-9, room temperature to 60\u00b0C, days timescale\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The delta-amino group of ornithine (pKa ~10.5) acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). The reaction proceeds through an addition-tautomerization mechanism: (1) The amine nitrogen attacks the nitrile carbon of cyanamide. (2) Proton transfer generates a guanidinium intermediate. (3) Tautomerization yields the thermodynamically stable guanidinium form of arginine. The delta-amino group is more reactive than the alpha-amino group because it is more nucleophilic (less electron-withdrawn) and less sterically hindered.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the most well-documented prebiotic route to arginine. Osterberg & Orgel (1972, Journal of Molecular Evolution) demonstrated that cyanamide reacts with ornithine under mild aqueous conditions to produce arginine in measurable yields. The selectivity for delta-amino over alpha-amino guanidination was confirmed. Or\u00f3 & Kimball (1961) also showed cyanamide as an effective guanidinating agent for amines. This reaction requires no mineral catalyst, no UV, and proceeds under ambient prebiotic conditions. It is the most defensible final step for arginine synthesis in any prebiotic network.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full rTCA hydrothermal pathway via direct CO2-to-pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct CO2 reduction to pyruvate on native iron (Varma et al.), followed by rTCA cycle to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation-assisted reduction to glutamate-5-semialdehyde, reductive amination to ornithine, and cyanamide guanidination. The cyanamide branch proceeds via HCN hydrolysis to cyanate, W\u00f6hler rearrangement to urea, and thermal dehydration to cyanamide. Strongest hydrothermal-surface-biochemical environmental flow.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-formaldehyde-glycolaldehyde buildup to pyruvate, then rTCA\",\n      \"description\": \"Stepwise C1 buildup: CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192glycolaldehyde\u2192pyruvate via carbonylation, then rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. This pathway uses defined C1\u2192C2\u2192C3 intermediates avoiding the single-step CO2\u2192pyruvate jump.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA with surface Strecker glutamate via decarboxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct CO2\u2192pyruvate, then rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate. Alpha-ketoglutarate is transported to surface environment where UV-driven oxidative decarboxylation produces succinic semialdehyde. Strecker synthesis (succinic semialdehyde + HCN + NH3) gives glutamate on the surface. Then phosphorylation-assisted route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"C1 buildup through pyruvate with Strecker glutamate branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Stepwise C1\u2192C2\u2192C3 buildup to pyruvate via formate/formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde, then rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate, decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde (surface), Strecker to glutamate, phosphorylation-assisted route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. Maximum number of defined intermediates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-hub HCN pathway: cyanide as both Strecker reagent and cyanamide source\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN serves dual roles: (1) as Strecker reagent for glutamate synthesis from succinic semialdehyde and (2) as precursor to cyanamide via hydrolysis\u2192cyanate\u2192urea\u2192cyanamide. Alpha-ketoglutarate is produced hydrothermally (direct pyruvate + rTCA), decarboxylated to succinic semialdehyde on surface, and Strecker chemistry completes glutamate synthesis. Conceptually elegant dual-use of HCN.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal hydrothermal pathway: direct pyruvate, direct reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Most streamlined pathway using the fewest reactions: direct CO2\u2192pyruvate (Varma), rTCA to \u03b1-KG, direct reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation and reduction to semialdehyde, amination to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. Avoids the Strecker branch entirely. Strongest literature support per reaction.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-carbonylation route with hydrothermal reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Emphasizes C1 chemistry: CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde via hydrothermal FTT, then surface aldol to glycolaldehyde, return to hydrothermal for carbonylation to pyruvate, rTCA to \u03b1-KG, reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. Best environmental cycling narrative (H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192H\u2192B\u2192S\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent dual-glutamate route: hydrothermal amination + surface Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate (from rTCA) serves as a divergence hub: one branch undergoes direct reductive amination to glutamate (hydrothermal), the other undergoes decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde then Strecker to glutamate (surface). Both glutamate sources converge at the phosphorylation step. Demonstrates redundancy in glutamate production. Uses direct pyruvate route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-dominated Strecker pathway with minimal hydrothermal input\",\n      \"description\": \"Minimizes hydrothermal steps: only CO2\u2192pyruvate and rTCA for alpha-ketoglutarate. All subsequent chemistry occurs on the surface or in biochemical pools: decarboxylation (UV), Strecker glutamate, phosphorylation on apatite, then return to hydrothermal for reduction of acyl phosphate, followed by biochemical amination and guanidination. Emphasizes surface chemistry contribution.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Full network traversal: C1 buildup + dual glutamate + cyanamide guanidination\",\n      \"description\": \"Maximum redundancy pathway that includes both pyruvate routes (direct and C1 buildup), both glutamate routes (reductive amination and Strecker), and the full cyanamide synthesis from HCN. Demonstrates the complete network topology by traversing every hub molecule. Not the most efficient route but shows how all branches interconnect.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate: convergence of direct CO2 reduction (rxn_002) and stepwise C1 buildup through glycolaldehyde carbonylation (rxn_005)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate: produced by rTCA reductive carboxylation of succinate (rxn_008); feeds both reductive amination to glutamate (rxn_009) and oxidative decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde (rxn_010)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate: convergence of hydrothermal reductive amination (rxn_009) and surface Strecker synthesis (rxn_011); feeds into phosphorylation route to ornithine\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"description\": \"Ornithine: produced by reductive amination of glutamate-5-semialdehyde (rxn_014); feeds into final guanidination to arginine (rxn_018)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN: starting material used in both Strecker synthesis of glutamate (rxn_011) and cyanamide production via hydrolysis-cyanate-urea pathway (rxn_015). Dual functional hub connecting surface chemistry.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network builds arginine through a multi-environment strategy with five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, ornithine). The key innovations addressing prior criticisms: (1) Ornithine is produced via a phosphorylation-assisted reduction of glutamate, where glutamyl-5-phosphate is formed on apatite under dry heat, then the activated acyl-phosphate is reduced on mackinawite/Fe\u2070 to glutamate-5-semialdehyde \u2014 this avoids the thermodynamically forbidden direct carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction. (2) Cyanamide is generated via well-documented thermal dehydration of urea (itself from ammonium cyanate rearrangement), avoiding the problematic HCN+NH3+UV route. (3) Pyruvate synthesis uses two documented routes: direct CO2 reduction on native iron (Varma et al., 2018) and stepwise C1 buildup through formate/formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde. (4) The rTCA partial cycle to alpha-ketoglutarate proceeds through explicit oxaloacetate and succinate intermediates with individual mineral catalysts specified. (5) An alternative Strecker route to glutamate bypasses the full rTCA by using succinic semialdehyde derived from decarboxylation of alpha-ketoglutarate. Ten pathways arise from combinatorial selection across two pyruvate routes, two alpha-ketoglutarate routes, two glutamate routes, and two cyanamide precursor routes, all converging through the ornithine hub.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "Ca5(PO4)3(OH)", "iupac_name": "hydroxylapatite", "common_name": "Apatite / Inorganic phosphate source", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "glycolaldehyde", "common_name": "Glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "3-carboxy-2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4-6)1-3(7)8/h1H2,(H,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "butanedioic acid", "common_name": "Succinate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "Alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "Glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H10NO7P", "iupac_name": "5-phospho-L-glutamate", "common_name": "Glutamyl-5-phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "Glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-5-7)8-9/h5H,1-3,6H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H12N2O2", "iupac_name": "(S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "Ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "urea", "common_name": "Urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "Cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "(S)-2-amino-5-guanidinopentanoic acid", "common_name": "Arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C4H7NO3", "iupac_name": "4-oxobutanoic acid, 2-amino-", "common_name": "Succinic semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "NH4OCN", "iupac_name": "ammonium cyanate", "common_name": "Ammonium cyanate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is adsorbed on Fe3S4 surface, where it undergoes a two-electron reduction by H2 to produce formate (HCOO\u207b). The greigite surface mimics the active site of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase. H2 dissociates on the FeS surface, providing hydride equivalents for CO2 reduction.", "reasoning": "Demonstrated experimentally by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) who showed CO2 reduction to formate on native iron and iron-nickel-sulfide precipitates under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions. Roldan et al. (2015, Chemical Communications) showed greigite specifically catalyzes CO2 reduction to formate at ambient temperature under alkaline conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Direct CO2 reduction to pyruvate on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>30 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe0, awaruite Fe3Ni) with magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH, CO2 saturated"}, "mechanism": "Native iron (Fe0) serves as a strong reductant, donating electrons to CO2. The reaction proceeds through multiple C-C bond forming steps on the iron surface: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO/formyl species \u2192 acetaldehyde/acetate \u2192 pyruvate. The iron surface provides both reducing power and a template for C-C bond formation via radical recombination.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron (Fe0) reduces CO2 to pyruvate, acetate, and other organic acids under hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, moderate pressures). Yields of pyruvate were significant. This represents a single-step fixation pathway from CO2 to a C3 alpha-keto acid, bypassing the need for stepwise C1 buildup. The native iron acts as both electron donor and surface catalyst."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-450K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite with trace native iron", "aqueous": true, "other": "Strongly reducing conditions, H2 excess"}, "mechanism": "Formate adsorbed on the magnetite surface undergoes partial reduction by H2. The Fe(II)/Fe(III) redox couple in magnetite mediates electron transfer. The O-H bond of formate is cleaved and the resulting formyl intermediate is protonated to yield formaldehyde. Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) chemistry on magnetite surfaces produces formaldehyde as a kinetic intermediate before further reduction to methanol.", "reasoning": "McCollom & Seewald (2003, Earth and Planetary Science Letters) demonstrated FTT synthesis on magnetite producing aldehydes and alcohols. He et al. (2019, ACS Central Science) showed that formaldehyde can be generated from CO/CO2 reduction under hydrothermal conditions. Formaldehyde is kinetically trapped at moderate temperatures before further reduction to methanol occurs. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under strongly reducing conditions with excess H2."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formaldehyde aldol condensation to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay with Ca(OH)2", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 10-12, Ca2+ ions present"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. Ca(OH)2 generates the enolizable species (Cannizzaro disproportionation provides formate + methanol, while the enolized formaldehyde attacks a second formaldehyde molecule). Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate formaldehyde and stabilize the glycolaldehyde product through adsorption, preventing further condensation to higher sugars.", "reasoning": "This is the first step of the formose reaction, well-documented by Breslow (1959). Weber (2001, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) showed that glycolaldehyde forms preferentially as the initial C2 product. Borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde, but at the clay surface the concentration effect prevents runaway polymerization (Scorei, 2012). Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) showed borate stabilization of sugars in formose-like systems."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Stepwise pyruvate synthesis from glycolaldehyde and CO via carbonylation", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>20 bar CO/CO2)", "catalyst": "greigite, iron-nickel sulfide surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "CO/CO2/H2 mixed gas phase, alkaline vent conditions"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde is oxidized to glyoxylate at the FeS2 surface. Glyoxylate then undergoes reductive carboxylation with CO2/CO on the Fe3S4 surface, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. CO binds to the iron-sulfur surface, forming a metal-carbonyl intermediate, which inserts into the C-H bond of glyoxylate to form pyruvate. Alternatively, glyoxylate condenses with formaldehyde and is then oxidized to pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Cody et al. (2000, Science) demonstrated pyruvate formation from C1-C2 precursors under hydrothermal conditions on FeS surfaces. Huber & Wachtershauser (1997, Science) showed carbonylation reactions on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces producing activated acyl species. The glycolaldehyde-to-pyruvate conversion through glyoxylate is consistent with the iron-sulfur world hypothesis and provides an explicit C2\u2192C3 buildup pathway with defined intermediates."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate (rTCA step)", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe3S4 / FeS with Cr(III) or Zn(II) cofactors", "aqueous": true, "other": "CO2-rich alkaline fluids, reducing environment"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is activated on the greigite surface and inserts into the C2-H bond of pyruvate via a carboxylation mechanism analogous to pyruvate carboxylase. The mineral surface stabilizes the enolpyruvate tautomer, facilitating nucleophilic attack on the electrophilic carbon of surface-bound CO2. This is the reverse of the oxidative decarboxylation of oxaloacetate.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that iron(0) promotes non-enzymatic analogs of TCA cycle reactions including the reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate. Varma et al. (2018) and Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed that Fe0/FeS promotes a network of rTCA reactions. Keller et al. (2014, Molecular Systems Biology) showed non-enzymatic rTCA-like reactions under volcanic aqueous conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Reduction of oxaloacetate to succinate via malate and fumarate (rTCA segment)", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0 with Fe3O4", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing conditions, H2 from serpentinization, intermediates: malate, fumarate"}, "mechanism": "Three-step reduction sequence: (1) Oxaloacetate is reduced to malate by H2 on Fe0 surface (keto reduction). (2) Malate dehydrates to fumarate on the mineral surface (elimination, thermally driven). (3) Fumarate is reduced to succinate by H2 on Fe0 (C=C reduction). These are individually documented steps of the reductive TCA cycle. The Fe0/magnetite surface catalyzes all three transformations.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated the complete non-enzymatic promotion of the reductive TCA cycle by metallic iron (Fe0) in water at 70-100\u00b0C. All three steps (OAA\u2192malate\u2192fumarate\u2192succinate) were observed with high yields. The reduction steps are thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions at hydrothermal vents where serpentinization generates abundant H2. Presented as a combined reaction node for network clarity, but proceeds through explicit malate and fumarate intermediates."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>20 bar)", "catalyst": "Fe0 with Fe3S4", "aqueous": true, "other": "CO2-saturated reducing solution, Zn2+ as possible cofactor"}, "mechanism": "Succinate is activated at one carboxyl terminus on the Fe3S4 surface. CO2 inserts via a radical or anionic mechanism to form the C5 skeleton of alpha-ketoglutarate. The FeS surface provides reducing equivalents to drive the thermodynamically uphill carboxylation through coupling to Fe0 oxidation. The reaction may proceed through succinyl-thioester intermediate on the sulfide surface.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed this reaction occurring as part of the non-enzymatic rTCA network on Fe0. The reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate is the key C4\u2192C5 chain extension of the rTCA cycle. Yield is lower than the OAA\u2192succinate steps but is detectible. Camprubi et al. (2019) proposed that the alkaline vent pH gradient provides additional thermodynamic driving force for this endergonic step. This is the most thermodynamically challenging step in the rTCA analog."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS with Fe0 as reductant", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH4+ from hydrothermal fluids, pH 6-9, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks the C2 keto group of alpha-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base). The imine is reduced by H2 (or surface-bound hydride on FeS) to yield glutamate. The FeS surface both catalyzes imine formation through Lewis acid activation of the ketone and provides reducing equivalents for imine reduction. This is a reductive amination, one of the most fundamental prebiotic amino acid forming reactions.", "reasoning": "Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) showed reductive amination of alpha-keto acids (including pyruvate to alanine) under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions using iron oxyhydroxide minerals. Wang et al. (2011) demonstrated similar reactions on FeS surfaces. Huber & Wachtershauser (2006) showed amino acid formation from alpha-keto acids and NH3 under volcanic conditions. The reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate is the most direct and thermodynamically favorable route to this amino acid."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Oxidative decarboxylation of alpha-ketoglutarate to succinic semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_001"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, aerobic-free but UV-driven oxidative decarboxylation"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoglutarate undergoes UV-photocatalyzed oxidative decarboxylation at C1-C2, losing CO2 and generating succinic semialdehyde (4-oxobutanoic acid). TiO2 generates reactive oxygen species under UV that abstract an electron from the alpha-keto group, facilitating decarboxylation. This is a thermodynamically favorable (exergonic) reaction driven by both UV energy and the stability of CO2.", "reasoning": "Oxidative decarboxylation of alpha-keto acids is thermodynamically spontaneous (\u0394G < 0) and occurs readily under UV irradiation. Rapf & Vaida (2016) documented photodegradation of alpha-keto acids including pyruvate under UV conditions relevant to early Earth. Alpha-ketoglutarate decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde is well-known in biochemistry and occurs non-enzymatically under oxidative or UV conditions. TiO2 photocatalysis of organic acid transformations is documented by Shkrob et al. (2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis of glutamate from succinic semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool conditions, concentrated HCN and NH3"}, "mechanism": "Classical Strecker synthesis: (1) Ammonia attacks the aldehyde of succinic semialdehyde to form an amino alcohol, then dehydrates to an imine. (2) HCN adds to the imine to form an alpha-aminonitrile (2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid is not formed; rather 2-amino-5-cyanopentanenitrile \u2014 correction: the Strecker adds HCN to give alpha-amino nitrile at the aldehyde carbon). (3) The nitrile is hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid (amide intermediate). Product is 2-aminopentanedioic acid = glutamic acid.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the best-documented prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Miller, 1953; Miller & Urey, 1959). The use of succinic semialdehyde (an aliphatic aldehyde with a pendant carboxyl group) as the substrate is a straightforward extension of Strecker chemistry to produce glutamate. Parker et al. (2011, Origins of Life) confirmed Strecker synthesis produces amino acids corresponding to the aldehyde substrate. This provides an alternative surface-chemistry route to glutamate that bypasses hydrothermal reductive amination."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Phosphorylation of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to glutamyl-5-phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "struvite (MgNH4PO4\u00b76H2O) or apatite", "aqueous": false, "other": "Dry-heat conditions during evaporitic cycle, 60-85\u00b0C, low water activity"}, "mechanism": "During the drying phase of a wet-dry cycle, glutamate and phosphate minerals are concentrated. At elevated temperature and low water activity, the gamma-carboxyl group of glutamate attacks the phosphorus of the mineral phosphate, forming a mixed anhydride (acyl phosphate) bond. The gamma-carboxyl is selectively phosphorylated over the alpha-carboxyl because it is less sterically hindered and not involved in intramolecular hydrogen bonding with the alpha-amino group. Struvite dissolves to provide reactive phosphate.", "reasoning": "Pasek et al. (2017, Angewandte Chemie) demonstrated phosphorylation of organic acids by reactive phosphorus minerals under mild heating. Burcar et al. (2016) showed dry-state phosphorylation of amino acids and organic acids on mineral surfaces. The formation of acyl phosphates from carboxylic acids and phosphate is well-documented under dehydrating conditions (Gibard et al., 2018, Nature Chemistry). The mixed anhydride (acyl phosphate) is the key activated intermediate that makes subsequent reduction feasible."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reductive dephosphorylation of glutamyl-5-phosphate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "FeS/Fe0 as reductant", "aqueous": true, "other": "Return to hydrothermal reducing conditions, H2-rich fluids, phosphate released and recycled"}, "mechanism": "The acyl phosphate bond of glutamyl-5-phosphate is a high-energy mixed anhydride (\u0394G\u00b0hydrolysis ~ -43 kJ/mol), making it thermodynamically activated for reduction. Fe0 or FeS donates two electrons to the acyl-phosphate carbon: the C-O(P) bond is cleaved, phosphate departs as a leaving group, and the carbonyl is reduced to the aldehyde oxidation state. This is analogous to the biological glutamate-5-phosphate reductase reaction but using mineral-surface electrons instead of NADPH. The acyl phosphate activation is the critical innovation: direct carboxyl reduction (\u0394G > +30 kJ/mol) is thermodynamically forbidden, but acyl phosphate reduction (\u0394G ~ -10 kJ/mol) is favorable.", "reasoning": "This phosphorylation-assisted reduction strategy mirrors the biological pathway (glutamate kinase \u2192 glutamate-5-phosphate reductase) and is the key solution to the problematic direct carboxyl-to-aldehyde reduction identified in previous attempts. Acyl phosphates are well-known activated carboxylic acid derivatives with reduction potentials approximately 400 mV more positive than free carboxylates (Pasek & Kee, 2011). Mullen & Sutherland (2007) discussed acyl phosphate intermediates in prebiotic context. The use of Fe0 as a two-electron reductant for activated substrates is consistent with Muchowska et al. (2019). The phosphate is released and recycled, consistent with catalytic phosphate cycling in prebiotic environments."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to ornithine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (spontaneous in NH3-rich solution), or pyridoxal as catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "Concentrated prebiotic pool, NH4+ at mM-M concentrations, mildly alkaline pH 8-9"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia (or ammonium ion) attacks the aldehyde carbon of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to form a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to give an imine (Schiff base). The imine is reduced to the amine: in prebiotic conditions, reduction can occur via (1) borohydride-like minerals, (2) transamination with another amino acid (e.g., alanine acting as amino donor), or (3) disproportionation where a second aldehyde molecule acts as hydride donor (Leuckart-Wallach type). Product is L-ornithine (2,5-diaminopentanoic acid).", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of aldehydes is one of the most facile prebiotic reactions. Glutamate-5-semialdehyde spontaneously cyclizes to \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate in aqueous solution, but in the presence of excess ammonia, the open-chain form is trapped as the imine and reduced to ornithine. This is documented in biochemistry as the ornithine aminotransferase reaction. Prebiotically, transamination with other amino acids (Wachtershauser, 2000) or reduction by thiols/FeS (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006) can drive the reaction. High ammonia concentrations in early Earth environments (Summers & Chang, 1993) favor the intermolecular amination product over cyclization."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Ammonium cyanate formation from HCN hydrolysis and NH3", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface for concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 8-10"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes base-catalyzed hydrolysis in alkaline solution: HCN + H2O \u2192 HOCN (cyanic acid/isocyanic acid). In the presence of ammonia, isocyanic acid is immediately trapped as ammonium cyanate (NH4OCN). The clay surface concentrates both HCN and NH3 and provides an alkaline microenvironment that favors hydrolysis over oligomerization.", "reasoning": "HCN hydrolysis to cyanate is well-documented in alkaline aqueous solution (Sanchez et al., 1967). The conversion of HCN to HNCO (isocyanic acid) and then to ammonium cyanate in ammonia-containing solutions is a standard aqueous chemistry reaction. Miyakawa et al. (2002) documented cyanate as a major product of HCN processing in prebiotic ocean simulants."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "W\u00f6hler synthesis: ammonium cyanate rearrangement to urea", "inputs": ["mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "thermal, clay surface assists concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool, heating during dry phase of wet-dry cycle"}, "mechanism": "Ammonium cyanate undergoes the classic W\u00f6hler rearrangement: NH4+ attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanate (OCN\u207b) intramolecularly, forming urea (H2N-CO-NH2). This is one of the oldest known organic reactions (W\u00f6hler, 1828). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds spontaneously at moderate temperatures. Concentration during evaporitic drying accelerates the reaction.", "reasoning": "The W\u00f6hler synthesis (1828) is the original demonstration of abiotic organic synthesis: ammonium cyanate \u2192 urea. This reaction is spontaneous and well-characterized kinetically (Shaw & Bordeaux, 1955). In prebiotic context, Menor-Salvan et al. (2009) showed urea formation from HCN-derived cyanate in simulated early Earth conditions. Urea is detected in Miller-Urey-type experiments and is a plausible prebiotic molecule."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Thermal dehydration of urea to cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface, dry heat", "aqueous": false, "other": "Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, volcanic hot spring margins, 80-130\u00b0C"}, "mechanism": "Urea undergoes thermal dehydration: the O-H bond of the enol tautomer breaks, and the C=O is converted to C=NH with loss of water, yielding cyanamide (H2N-CN). This proceeds at temperatures above ~80\u00b0C under dry conditions. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the reaction by stabilizing the transition state through surface interactions. An alternative pathway involves initial isomerization to carbodiimide (HN=C=NH) followed by tautomerization to cyanamide.", "reasoning": "Schimpl et al. (1965) and Lohrmann & Orgel (1968) documented thermal decomposition of urea to cyanamide under dry-heating conditions at 80-130\u00b0C. Gabel & Ponnamperuma (1967) showed urea decomposition products include cyanamide and biuret. This is a well-established thermal reaction. Cyanamide is a key prebiotic condensing agent and guanidinium donor, documented extensively by Orgel and colleagues. The generation of cyanamide from urea via thermal dehydration is a robust, well-characterized prebiotic reaction with no significant mechanistic ambiguity."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide to form arginine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required", "aqueous": true, "other": "Concentrated prebiotic pool, pH 7-9, room temperature to 60\u00b0C, days timescale"}, "mechanism": "The delta-amino group of ornithine (pKa ~10.5) acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). The reaction proceeds through an addition-tautomerization mechanism: (1) The amine nitrogen attacks the nitrile carbon of cyanamide. (2) Proton transfer generates a guanidinium intermediate. (3) Tautomerization yields the thermodynamically stable guanidinium form of arginine. The delta-amino group is more reactive than the alpha-amino group because it is more nucleophilic (less electron-withdrawn) and less sterically hindered.", "reasoning": "This is the most well-documented prebiotic route to arginine. Osterberg & Orgel (1972, Journal of Molecular Evolution) demonstrated that cyanamide reacts with ornithine under mild aqueous conditions to produce arginine in measurable yields. The selectivity for delta-amino over alpha-amino guanidination was confirmed. Or\u00f3 & Kimball (1961) also showed cyanamide as an effective guanidinating agent for amines. This reaction requires no mineral catalyst, no UV, and proceeds under ambient prebiotic conditions. It is the most defensible final step for arginine synthesis in any prebiotic network."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full rTCA hydrothermal pathway via direct CO2-to-pyruvate", "description": "Direct CO2 reduction to pyruvate on native iron (Varma et al.), followed by rTCA cycle to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation-assisted reduction to glutamate-5-semialdehyde, reductive amination to ornithine, and cyanamide guanidination. The cyanamide branch proceeds via HCN hydrolysis to cyanate, W\u00f6hler rearrangement to urea, and thermal dehydration to cyanamide. Strongest hydrothermal-surface-biochemical environmental flow.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Formate-formaldehyde-glycolaldehyde buildup to pyruvate, then rTCA", "description": "Stepwise C1 buildup: CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde\u2192glycolaldehyde\u2192pyruvate via carbonylation, then rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate, reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. This pathway uses defined C1\u2192C2\u2192C3 intermediates avoiding the single-step CO2\u2192pyruvate jump.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal rTCA with surface Strecker glutamate via decarboxylation", "description": "Direct CO2\u2192pyruvate, then rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate. Alpha-ketoglutarate is transported to surface environment where UV-driven oxidative decarboxylation produces succinic semialdehyde. Strecker synthesis (succinic semialdehyde + HCN + NH3) gives glutamate on the surface. Then phosphorylation-assisted route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_021", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "C1 buildup through pyruvate with Strecker glutamate branch", "description": "Stepwise C1\u2192C2\u2192C3 buildup to pyruvate via formate/formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde, then rTCA to alpha-ketoglutarate, decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde (surface), Strecker to glutamate, phosphorylation-assisted route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. Maximum number of defined intermediates.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_021", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Dual-hub HCN pathway: cyanide as both Strecker reagent and cyanamide source", "description": "HCN serves dual roles: (1) as Strecker reagent for glutamate synthesis from succinic semialdehyde and (2) as precursor to cyanamide via hydrolysis\u2192cyanate\u2192urea\u2192cyanamide. Alpha-ketoglutarate is produced hydrothermally (direct pyruvate + rTCA), decarboxylated to succinic semialdehyde on surface, and Strecker chemistry completes glutamate synthesis. Conceptually elegant dual-use of HCN.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_013", "mol_021", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Minimal hydrothermal pathway: direct pyruvate, direct reductive amination", "description": "Most streamlined pathway using the fewest reactions: direct CO2\u2192pyruvate (Varma), rTCA to \u03b1-KG, direct reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation and reduction to semialdehyde, amination to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. Avoids the Strecker branch entirely. Strongest literature support per reaction.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Formose-carbonylation route with hydrothermal reductive amination", "description": "Emphasizes C1 chemistry: CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde via hydrothermal FTT, then surface aldol to glycolaldehyde, return to hydrothermal for carbonylation to pyruvate, rTCA to \u03b1-KG, reductive amination to glutamate, phosphorylation route to ornithine, cyanamide guanidination. Best environmental cycling narrative (H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192H\u2192B\u2192S\u2192S\u2192S\u2192B).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Convergent dual-glutamate route: hydrothermal amination + surface Str